# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aloha-festivals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] The **Aloha Festivals** are an annual series of free cultural celebrations observed in the state of Hawaii in the United States based on the Makahiki, the beginning of the Native Hawaiian year marked by the sighting of the Pleiades (*Makali'i*).
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] It is the only statewide cultural festival in the nation.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] Highlights include the presentation of the Royal Court, a ho'olaule'a in Waikiki, and the Floral Parade.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] Approximately 30,000 people volunteer to plan, organize, and provide labor for the Aloha Festivals each year.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] Their efforts entertain over 1,000,000 people from throughout the state and visitors from all over the world.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] In the spirit of preserving the Hawaiian culture and heritage, the Aloha Festivals were established in 1946 as **Aloha Week** by former members of the local Junior Chamber of Commerce.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] The former manager of the festivals, Goriann Akau, has said, "In 1946, after the war, Hawaiians needed an identity.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] When we started to celebrate our culture, we began to feel proud.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] We have a wonderful culture that had been buried for a number of years.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] The festival was celebrated on six of Hawaii's islands, but in 2008 festival organizers decided to hold most events on Oahu due to a lack of funding.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] There was also the chance that the Floral Parade would be cancelled altogether, but it was saved by private donors and funds from the City and County of Honolulu.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] That was caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, a year which had many disruptions.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] The court is selected from a pool of applicants, all of whom must be of Hawaiian ancestry and of certain ages.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] The festival itself begins with the presentation of the royal court during the opening ceremony.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] The ceremony takes place at Helumoa, a section of Waikiki near the Royal Hawaiian Center.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] The Floral Parade starts at the intersection of Ala Moana Boulevard and Kamakee st. and goes through Waikiki before finishing at Kapiolani Park.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] The parade features p'au riders, marching bands, hula halaus, and that year's Aloha Festival Royal Court.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] The Hoʻolauleʻa is a block party held in Waikiki.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] There is Hawaiian music, hula, and food.
[src:aloha-festivals/aloha-festivals] Attendance is typically in the thousands.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The global **COVID-19 pandemic** (also known as the **coronavirus pandemic**), caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2), began with an outbreak in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It spread to other parts of Asia and then worldwide in early 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) declared the outbreak a public health emergency of international concern (PHEIC) on 30 January 2020 and assessed it as having become a pandemic on 11 March.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO declared that the public health emergency caused by COVID-19 had ended in May 2023, while noting that COVID-19 continued to be a global health threat.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] COVID-19 symptoms range from asymptomatic to deadly, but most commonly include fever, sore throat, nocturnal cough, and fatigue.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Transmission of the virus is often through airborne particles.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Mutations have produced many strains (variants) with varying degrees of infectivity and virulence.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] COVID-19 vaccines were developed rapidly and deployed to the general public beginning in December 2020, made available through government and international programmes such as COVAX, aiming to provide vaccine equity.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Treatments include novel antiviral drugs and symptom control.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Common mitigation measures during the public health emergency included travel restrictions, lockdowns, business restrictions and closures, workplace hazard controls, mask mandates, quarantines, testing systems, and contact tracing of the infected.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The pandemic caused severe social and economic disruption around the world, including the largest global recession since the Great Depression.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Widespread supply shortages, including food shortages, were caused by supply chain disruptions and panic buying.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Reduced human activity led to an unprecedented temporary decrease in pollution.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Educational institutions and public areas were partially or fully closed in many jurisdictions, and many events were cancelled or postponed during 2020 and 2021.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Telework became much more common for white-collar workers as the pandemic evolved.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Misinformation circulated through social media and occasionally through mass media, and political tensions intensified.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The pandemic raised issues of racial and geographic discrimination, health equity, and the balance between public health imperatives and individual rights.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The disease has continued to circulate since 2023.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Different definitions of pandemics lead to different determinations of when they end.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 6 June 2026, COVID-19 has caused 7,114,321 confirmed deaths and 18.5 to 35.2 million estimated deaths.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The pandemic was the fifth-deadliest pandemic or epidemic in history.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In epidemiology, a pandemic is defined as "an epidemic occurring over a very wide area, crossing international boundaries, and usually affecting a large number of people".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, as with other pandemics, the meaning of this term has been challenged.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The end of a pandemic or other epidemic only rarely involves the total disappearance of a disease, and historically, much less attention has been given to defining the ends of epidemics than their beginnings.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The ends of particular epidemics have been defined in a variety of ways, differing according to academic field, and differently based on location and social group.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] An epidemic's end can be considered a social phenomenon, not just a biological one.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] During the initial outbreak in Wuhan, the virus and disease were commonly referred to as "coronavirus", "Wuhan coronavirus", "the coronavirus outbreak" and the "Wuhan coronavirus outbreak", with the disease sometimes called "Wuhan pneumonia".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In January 2020, the WHO recommended 2019-nCoV and 2019-nCoV acute respiratory disease as interim names for the virus and disease per 2015 international guidelines against using geographical locations (e.g.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Wuhan, China), animal species, or groups of people in disease and virus names in part to prevent social stigma.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO finalised the official names COVID-19 and SARS-CoV-2 on 11 February 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] WHO Director-General Tedros Ghebreyesus explained: CO for *corona*, VI for *virus*, D for *disease* and 19 for when the outbreak was first identified (31 December 2019).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO additionally uses "the COVID-19 virus" and "the virus responsible for COVID-19" in public communications.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO named variants of concern and variants of interest using Greek letters.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The initial practice of naming them according to where the variants were identified (e.g.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Delta began as the "Indian variant") is no longer common.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A more systematic naming scheme reflects the variant's PANGO lineage (e.g., Omicron's lineage is B.1.1.529) and is used for other variants.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] SARS-CoV-2 is a virus closely related to bat coronaviruses, pangolin coronaviruses, and SARS-CoV.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The first known outbreak (the 2019–2020 COVID-19 outbreak in mainland China) started in Wuhan, Hubei, China, in December 2019.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many early cases were linked to people who had visited the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market there, but it is possible that human-to-human transmission began earlier.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Molecular clock analysis suggests that the first cases were likely to have been between October and November 2019.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The scientific consensus is that the virus is most likely of a zoonotic origin, from bats or another closely related mammal.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] While other explanations, such as speculations that SARS-CoV-2 was accidentally released from a laboratory, have been proposed, as of 2021 these were not sufficiently supported by evidence.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Official "case" counts refer to the number of people who have been tested for COVID-19 and whose test has been confirmed positive according to official protocols whether they experienced symptomatic disease.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Due to the effect of sampling bias, studies which obtain a more accurate number by extrapolating from a random sample have consistently found that total infections considerably exceed the reported case counts.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many countries, early on, had official policies to not test those with only mild symptoms.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The strongest risk factors for severe illness are obesity, complications of diabetes, anxiety disorders, and the total number of conditions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] During the start of the COVID-19 pandemic, it was not clear whether young people were less likely to be infected, or less likely to develop symptoms and be tested.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A retrospective cohort study in China found that children and adults were just as likely to be infected.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Among more thorough studies, preliminary results from 9 April 2020 found that in Gangelt, the centre of a major infection cluster in Germany, 15 per cent of a population sample tested positive for antibodies.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Screening for COVID-19 in pregnant women in New York City, and blood donors in the Netherlands, found rates of positive antibody tests that indicated more infections than reported.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Seroprevalence-based estimates are conservative as some studies show that persons with mild symptoms do not have detectable antibodies.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Initial estimates of the basic reproduction number (R0) for COVID-19 in January 2020 were between 1.4 and 2.5, but a subsequent analysis claimed that it may be about 5.7 (with a 95 per cent confidence interval of 3.8 to 8.9).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In December 2021, the number of cases continued to climb due to several factors, including new COVID-19 variants.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of that 28 December, 282,790,822 individuals worldwide had been confirmed as infected.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 14 April 2022, over 500 million cases were confirmed globally.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Most cases are unconfirmed, with the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation estimating the true number of cases as of early 2022 to be in the billions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] One measure that public health officials and policymakers have used to monitor the pandemic and guide decision-making is the test positivity rate ("percent positive").
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] According to Johns Hopkins in 2020, one benchmark for a "too high" per cent positive is 5%, which was used by the WHO in the past.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 10 March 2023, more than 6.88 million deaths had been attributed to COVID-19.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The first confirmed death was in Wuhan on 9 January 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] These numbers vary by region and over time, influenced by testing volume, healthcare system quality, treatment options, government response, time since the initial outbreak, and population characteristics, such as age, sex, and overall health.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Multiple measures are used to quantify mortality.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Official death counts typically include people who died after testing positive.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Such counts exclude deaths without a test.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Conversely, deaths of people who died from underlying conditions following a positive test may be included.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Countries such as Belgium include deaths from suspected cases, including those without a test, thereby increasing counts.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Official death counts have been claimed to underreport the actual death toll, because excess mortality (the number of deaths in a period compared to a long-term average) data show an increase in deaths that is not explained by COVID-19 deaths alone.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Such deaths include deaths due to healthcare capacity constraints and priorities, as well as reluctance to seek care (to avoid possible infection).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Further research may help distinguish the proportions directly caused by COVID-19 from those caused by indirect consequences of the pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In May 2022, the WHO estimated the number of excess deaths by the end of 2021 to be 14.9 million compared to 5.4 million reported COVID-19 deaths, with the majority of the unreported 9.5 million deaths believed to be direct deaths due to the virus, rather than indirect deaths.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Some deaths were because people with other conditions could not access medical services.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A December 2022 WHO study estimated excess deaths from the pandemic during 2020 and 2021, again concluding ≈14.8 million excess early deaths occurred, reaffirming and detailing their prior calculations from May as well as updating them, addressing criticisms.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] These numbers do not include measures like years of potential life lost and may make the pandemic 2021's leading cause of death.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The time between symptom onset and death ranges from 6 to 41 days, typically about 14 days.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Mortality rates increase as a function of age.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] People at the greatest mortality risk are the elderly and those with underlying conditions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The infection fatality ratio (IFR) is the cumulative number of deaths attributed to the disease divided by the cumulative number of infected individuals (including asymptomatic and undiagnosed infections and excluding vaccinated infected individuals).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Other studies refer to this metric as the *infection fatality risk*.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In November 2020, a review article in *Nature* reported estimates of population-weighted IFRs for various countries, excluding deaths in elderly care facilities, and found a median range of 0.24% to 1.49%.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] These rates vary by a factor of ≈10,000 across the age groups.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] For comparison, the IFR for middle-aged adults is two orders of magnitude higher than the annualised risk of a fatal automobile accident and much higher than the risk of dying from seasonal influenza.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In December 2020, a systematic review and meta-analysis estimated that population-weighted IFR was 0.5% to 1% in some countries (France, Netherlands, New Zealand, and Portugal), 1% to 2% in other countries (Australia, England, Lithuania, and Spain), and about 2.5% in Italy.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] This study reported that most of the differences reflected corresponding differences in the population's age structure and the age-specific pattern of infections.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] There have also been reviews that have compared the fatality rate of this pandemic with prior pandemics, such as MERS-CoV.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] For comparison the infection mortality rate of seasonal flu in the United States is 0.1%, which is 13 times lower than COVID-19.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Another metric in assessing death rate is the case fatality ratio (CFR), which is the ratio of deaths to diagnoses.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] This metric can be misleading because of the delay between symptom onset and death and because testing focuses on symptomatic individuals.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Based on Johns Hopkins University statistics, the global CFR was 1.02 percent (6,881,955 deaths for 676,609,955 cases) as of 10 March 2023.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The number varies by region and has generally declined over time.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Several variants have been named by WHO and labelled as a variant of concern (VoC) or a variant of interest (VoI).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many of these variants have shared the more infectious D614G.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of May 2023, the WHO had downgraded all variants of concern to previously circulating as these were no longer detected in new infections.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Sub-lineages of the Omicron variant (BA.1 – BA.5) were considered separate VoCs by the WHO until they were downgraded in March 2023 as no longer widely circulating.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 24 September 2024, the variants of interest as specified by the WHO are BA.2.86 and JN.1, and the variants under monitoring are JN.1.7, KP.2, KP.3, KP.3.1.1, JN.1.18, LB.1, and XEC.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Symptoms of COVID-19 are variable, ranging from mild symptoms to severe illness.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Common symptoms include headache, loss of smell and taste, nasal congestion and runny nose, cough, muscle pain, sore throat, fever, diarrhoea, and breathing difficulties.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] People with the same infection may have different symptoms, and their symptoms may change over time.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In people without prior ear, nose, and throat disorders, loss of taste combined with loss of smell is associated with COVID-19 and is reported in as many as 88% of cases.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The disease is mainly transmitted via the respiratory route when people inhale droplets and small airborne particles (that form an aerosol) that infected people exhale as they breathe, talk, cough, sneeze, or sing.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Infected people are more likely to transmit COVID-19 when they are physically close to other non-infected individuals.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] However, infection can occur over longer distances, particularly indoors.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] SARS‑CoV‑2 belongs to the broad family of viruses known as coronaviruses.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It is a positive-sense single-stranded RNA (+ssRNA) virus, with a single linear RNA segment.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Coronaviruses infect humans, other mammals, including livestock and companion animals, and avian species.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Human coronaviruses are capable of causing illnesses ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS, fatality rate ≈34%).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] SARS-CoV-2 is the seventh known coronavirus to infect people, after 229E, NL63, OC43, HKU1, MERS-CoV, and the original SARS-CoV.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The standard method of testing for presence of SARS-CoV-2 is a nucleic acid test, which detects the presence of viral RNA fragments.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As these tests detect RNA but not infectious virus, its "ability to determine duration of infectivity of patients is limited".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The test is typically done on respiratory samples obtained by a nasopharyngeal swab; however, a nasal swab or sputum sample may also be used.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO has published several testing protocols for the disease.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A COVID-19 vaccine is intended to provide acquired immunity against severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS‑CoV‑2), the virus that causes coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Prior to the COVID-19 pandemic, an established body of knowledge existed about the structure and function of coronaviruses causing diseases like severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) and Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] This knowledge accelerated the development of various vaccine platforms during early 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The initial focus of SARS-CoV-2 vaccines was on preventing symptomatic and severe illness.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The COVID-19 vaccines are widely credited for their role in reducing the severity and death caused by COVID-19.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of August 2024, more than 5.6 billion people had received one or more doses (13.7 billion in total).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The Oxford-AstraZeneca vaccine was the most widely used.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] According to a June 2022 study, COVID-19 vaccines prevented an additional 14.4 million to 19.8 million deaths in 185 countries and territories from 8 December 2020 to 8 December 2021.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In 2022, the first recombinant protein-based COVID-19 vaccine (the Novavax vaccine) was authorised for use in adults in the United Kingdom.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It has subsequently received endorsement/authorisation from the WHO, US, European Union, and Australia.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] That same year also saw the first inhalable vaccine, developed by Chinese biopharmaceutical company CanSino Biologics.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] High-income countries rapidly bought up vaccines at the start of the pandemic, leading to concerns about vaccine equity.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By April 2021, one in 500 people in low and middle-income countries had been vaccinated, compared with one in four in high-income countries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] For the first two years of the pandemic, no specific and effective treatment or cure was available.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In 2021, the European Medicines Agency's (EMA) Committee for Medicinal Products for Human Use (CHMP) approved the oral antiviral protease inhibitor, Paxlovid (nirmatrelvir plus the HIV antiviral ritonavir), to treat adult patients.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In these, supportive care includes medication such as paracetamol or NSAIDs to relieve symptoms (fever, body aches, cough), adequate intake of oral fluids and rest.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Good personal hygiene and a healthy diet are also recommended.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Supportive care in severe cases includes treatment to relieve symptoms, fluid therapy, oxygen support and prone positioning, and medications or devices to support other affected vital organs.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] More severe cases may need treatment in hospital.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In those with low oxygen levels, use of the glucocorticoid dexamethasone is recommended to reduce mortality.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Noninvasive ventilation and, ultimately, admission to an intensive care unit for mechanical ventilation may be required to support breathing.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) has been used to address the issue of respiratory failure.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Existing drugs such as hydroxychloroquine, lopinavir/ritonavir, and ivermectin are not recommended by US or European health authorities, as there is no good evidence they have any useful effect.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The antiviral remdesivir is available in the US, Canada, Australia, and several other countries, with varying restrictions; however, it is not recommended for use with mechanical ventilation, and is discouraged altogether by the WHO, due to limited evidence of its efficacy.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It may take a mild course with few or no symptoms, resembling other common upper respiratory diseases such as the common cold.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In 3–4% of cases (7.4% for those over age 65) symptoms are severe enough to cause hospitalisation.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Mild cases typically recover within two weeks, while those with severe or critical diseases may take three to six weeks to recover.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Among those who have died, the time from symptom onset to death has ranged from two to eight weeks.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Prolonged prothrombin time and elevated C-reactive protein levels on admission to the hospital are associated with severe course of COVID-19 and with a transfer to intensive care units (ICU).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Between 5% and 50% of COVID-19 patients experience long COVID, a condition characterised by long-term consequences persisting after the typical convalescence period of the disease.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The most commonly reported clinical presentations are fatigue and memory problems, as well as malaise, headaches, shortness of breath, loss of smell, muscle weakness, low fever and cognitive dysfunction.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many countries attempted to slow or stop the spread of COVID-19 by recommending, mandating or prohibiting behaviour changes, while others relied primarily on providing information.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Measures ranged from public advisories to stringent lockdowns.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Outbreak control strategies are divided into elimination and mitigation.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] These initial strategies can be pursued sequentially or simultaneously during the acquired immunity phase through natural and vaccine-induced immunity.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Containment is undertaken to stop an outbreak from spreading into the general population.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Infected individuals are isolated while they are infectious.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The people they have interacted with are contacted and isolated for long enough to ensure that they are either not infected or no longer contagious.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Screening is the starting point for containment.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Screening is done by checking for symptoms to identify infected individuals, who can then be isolated or offered treatment.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Successful containment or suppression reduces Rt to less than 1.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Should containment fail, efforts focus on mitigation: measures taken to slow the spread and limit its effects on the healthcare system and society.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Successful mitigation delays and decreases the epidemic peak, known as "flattening the epidemic curve".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] This decreases the risk of overwhelming health services and provides more time for developing vaccines and treatments.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Individual behaviour changed in many jurisdictions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Many people worked from home instead of at their traditional workplaces.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] More drastic actions, such as quarantining entire populations and strict travel bans have been attempted in various jurisdictions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The Chinese and Australian government approaches have included many lockdowns and are widely considered the most strict.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The New Zealand government response included the most severe travel restrictions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As part of its K-Quarantine programme, South Korea introduced mass screening and localised quarantines, and issued alerts on the movements of infected individuals.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The Singaporean government's response included so-called "circuit breaker lockdowns" and financial support for those affected while also imposing large fines for those who broke quarantine.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Contact tracing attempts to identify recent contacts of newly infected individuals, and to screen them for infection; the traditional approach is to request a list of contacts from infectees, and then telephone or visit the contacts.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Contact tracing was widely used during the Western African Ebola virus epidemic in 2014.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Another approach is to collect location data from mobile devices to identify those who have come in significant contact with infectees, which prompted privacy concerns.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 10 April 2020, Google and Apple announced an initiative for privacy-preserving contact tracing.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In Europe and in the US, Palantir Technologies initially provided COVID-19 tracking services.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] WHO described increasing capacity and adapting healthcare as a fundamental mitigation.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The pandemic drove widespread adoption of telehealth.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Due to supply chain capacity limitations, some manufacturers began 3D printing material such as nasal swabs and ventilator parts.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In one example, an Italian startup received legal threats due to alleged patent infringement after reverse-engineering and printing one hundred requested ventilator valves overnight.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Individuals and groups of makers created and shared open source designs, and manufacturing devices using locally sourced materials, sewing, and 3D printing.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Millions of face shields, protective gowns, and masks were made.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Other ad hoc medical supplies included shoe covers, surgical caps, powered air-purifying respirators, and hand sanitiser.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Novel devices were created such as ear savers, non-invasive ventilation helmets, and ventilator splitters.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In July 2021, several experts expressed concern that achieving herd immunity may not be possible because Delta can transmit among vaccinated individuals.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] CDC published data showing that vaccinated people could transmit Delta, something officials believed was less likely with other variants.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Consequently, WHO and CDC encouraged vaccinated people to continue with non-pharmaceutical interventions such as masking, social distancing, and quarantining if exposed.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The outbreak was discovered in Wuhan in November 2019.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It is possible that human-to-human transmission was happening before the discovery.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Based on a retrospective analysis starting from December 2019, the number of cases in Hubei gradually increased, reaching 60 by 20 December and at least 266 by 31 December.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A pneumonia cluster was observed on 26 December and treated by Chinese pulmonologist Zhang Jixian.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] She informed the Wuhan Jianghan CDC on 27 December.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] After analysing pneumonia patient samples, a genetic sequencing company named Vision Medicals reported the discovery of a novel coronavirus to the China CDC (CCDC) on 28 December.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Two days later, a test report from CapitalBio Medlab addressed to the Wuhan Central Hospital reported an erroneous positive result for SARS, causing doctors there to alert authorities.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Eight of those doctors, including ophthalmologist Li Wenliang (1985–2020), were detained by police on 3 January for "spreading false rumours".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] That evening, Wuhan Municipal Health Commission (WMHC) issued a notice about "the treatment of pneumonia of unknown cause".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The next day, WMHC made the announcement public, confirming 27 cases—enough to trigger an investigation.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 31 December, the WHO office in China was notified about the cluster of unknown pneumonia cases and immediately launched an investigation.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Official Chinese sources claimed that the early cases were mostly linked to the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market, which also sold live animals.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In May 2020, CCDC director George Gao initially ruled out the market as a possible origin, as animal samples collected there had tested negative.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 11 January, WHO was notified by the Chinese National Health Commission that the outbreak was associated with exposures in the market, and that China had identified a new type of coronavirus, which it isolated on 7 January.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Initially, the number of cases doubled approximately every seven and a half days.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In early and mid-January, the virus spread to other Chinese provinces, helped by the Chinese New Year migration.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Wuhan was a transport hub and major rail interchange.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 10 January, the virus' genome was shared publicly.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A retrospective study published in March found that 6,174 people had reported symptoms by 20 January.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] A 24 January report indicated human transmission was likely occurring, and recommended personal protective equipment for health workers.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It also advocated testing, given the outbreak's "pandemic potential".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 30 January, 7,818 infections had been confirmed, leading WHO to declare the outbreak a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC), upgrading it to a pandemic on 11 March.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 31 January, the first published modelling study warned of inevitable "independent self-sustaining outbreaks in major cities globally" and called for "large-scale public health interventions".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 31 January, Italy indicated its first confirmed infections had occurred, in two tourists from China.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 19 March, Italy overtook China as the country with the most reported deaths.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 26 March, the United States had overtaken China and Italy as the country with the highest number of confirmed infections.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Genomic analysis indicated that the majority of New York's confirmed infections came from Europe, rather than directly from Asia.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Testing of prior samples revealed a person who was infected in France on 27 December 2019 and a person in the United States who died from the disease on 6 February.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In October, WHO reported that one in ten people around the world may have been infected, or 780 million people, while only 35 million infections had been confirmed.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 9 November, Pfizer released trial results for a candidate vaccine, showing a 90 per cent effectiveness in preventing infection.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] That day, Novavax submitted an FDA Fast Track application for their vaccine.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 14 December, Public Health England reported that a variant had been discovered in the UK's southeast, predominantly in Kent.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The variant, later named Alpha, showed changes to the spike protein that could make the virus more infectious.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] As of 13 December, 1,108 infections had been confirmed in the UK.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 4 February 2020, US Secretary of Health and Human Services Alex Azar waived liability for vaccine manufacturers in all cases except those involving "willful misconduct".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 2 January, the Alpha variant, first discovered in the UK, had been identified in 33 countries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 6 January, the Gamma variant was first identified in Japanese travellers returning from Brazil.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 29 January, it was reported that the Novavax vaccine was 49 per cent effective against the Beta variant in a clinical trial in South Africa.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The CoronaVac vaccine was reported to be 50.4 per cent effective in a Brazil clinical trial.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 12 March, several countries stopped using the Oxford–AstraZeneca COVID-19 vaccine due to blood clotting problems, specifically cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (CVST).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 20 March, the WHO and European Medicines Agency found no link to thrombosis, leading several countries to resume administering the vaccine.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In March WHO reported that an animal host was the most likely origin, without ruling out other possibilities.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The Delta variant was first identified in India.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In mid-April, the variant was first detected in the UK and two months later it had become a full-fledged third wave in the country, forcing the government to delay reopening that was originally scheduled for June.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 10 November, Germany advised against the Moderna vaccine for people under 30, due to a possible association with myocarditis.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 24 November, the Omicron variant was detected in South Africa; a few days later the WHO declared it a VoC (variant of concern).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The new variant is more infectious than the Delta variant.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 1 January, Europe passed 100 million cases amidst a surge in the Omicron variant.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Later that month, the WHO recommended the rheumatoid arthritis drug Baricitinib for severe or critical patients.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] It also recommended the monoclonal antibody Sotrovimab in patients with non-severe disease, but only those who are at highest risk of hospitalisation.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 24 January, the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation estimated that about 57% of the world's population had been infected by COVID-19.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 6 March, it was reported that the total worldwide death count had surpassed 6 million people.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 6 July, Omicron subvariants BA.4 and BA.5 had spread worldwide.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] WHO Director-General Tedros Ghebreyesus stated on 14 September 2022, that "[The world has] never been in a better position to end the pandemic", citing the lowest number of weekly reported deaths since March 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] But the end is in sight—we can see the finish line".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 21 October, the United States surpassed 99 million cases of COVID-19, the most cases of any country.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] By 30 October, the worldwide daily death toll was 424, the lowest since 385 deaths were reported on 12 March 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] 17 November marked the three-year anniversary since health officials in China first detected COVID-19.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 11 November, the WHO reported that deaths since the month of February had dropped 90 per cent.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Director-General Tedros said this was "cause for optimism".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 3 December, the WHO indicated that, "at least 90% of the world's population has some level of immunity to Sars-CoV-2".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In early December, China began lifting some of its most stringent lockdown measures.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Subsequent data from China's health authorities revealed that 248 million people, nearly 18 per cent of its population, had been infected in the first 20 days of that month.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 29 December, the US joined Italy, Japan, Taiwan and India in requiring negative COVID-19 test results from all people travelling from China due to the new surge in cases.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The EU refused similar measures, stating that the BF7 omicron variant had already spread throughout Europe without becoming dominant.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 4 January 2023, the WHO said the information shared by China during the recent surge in infections lacked data, such as hospitalisation rates.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 10 January, the WHO's Europe office said the recent viral surge in China posed "no immediate threat." On 16 January, the WHO recommended that China monitor excess mortality to provide "a more comprehensive understanding of the impact of COVID-19".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 30 January, the three-year anniversary of the original declaration, the WHO determined that COVID-19 still met the criteria for a public health emergency of international concern (PHEIC).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 19 March, WHO Director-General Tedros indicated he was "confident" the COVID-19 pandemic would cease to be a public health emergency by the end of the year.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] On 5 May, the WHO downgraded COVID-19 from being a global health emergency, though it continued to refer to it as a pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] The WHO does not make official declarations of when pandemics end.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Tedros agreed, and the WHO reduced the classification to an "established and ongoing health issue".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In a press conference, Tedros remarked that the diminishing threat from COVID-19 had "allowed most countries to return to life as we knew it before COVID-19".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In September the WHO said it had observed "concerning" trends in COVID-19 case numbers and hospitalisations, although analysis was hampered because many countries were no longer recording COVID-19 case statistics.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] In November 2023, in response to viral mutations and changing characteristics of infection, the WHO adjusted its treatment guidelines.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p01] Among other changes, remdesivir and molnupiravir were now recommended only for the most severe cases, and deuremidevir and ivermectin were recommended against.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] National reactions ranged from strict lockdowns to public education campaigns.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] WHO recommended that curfews and lockdowns should be short-term measures to reorganise, regroup, rebalance resources, and protect the health care system.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of 26 March 2020, 1.7 billion people worldwide were under some form of lockdown.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This increased to 3.9 billion people by the first week of April—more than half the world's population.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In several countries, protests rose against restrictions such as lockdowns.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A February 2021 study found that protests against restrictions were likely to directly increase the spread of the virus.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of the end of 2021, Asia's peak had come at the same time and at the same level as the world as a whole, in May 2021.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] However, cumulatively they had experienced only half of the global average in cases.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] China opted for containment, instituting strict lockdowns to eliminate viral spread.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The vaccines distributed in China included the BIBP, WIBP, and CoronaVac.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] It was reported on 11 December 2021, that China had vaccinated 1.162 billion of its citizens, or 82.5% of the total population of the country against COVID-19.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] China's large-scale adoption of zero-COVID had largely contained the first waves of infections of the disease.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] When the waves of infections due to the Omicron variant followed, China was almost alone in pursuing the strategy of zero-Covid to combat the spread of the virus in 2022.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Lockdown continued to be employed in November to combat a new wave of cases; however, protests erupted in cities across China over the country's stringent measures, and in December that year, the country relaxed its zero-COVID policy.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The first case in India was reported on 30 January 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] India ordered a nationwide lockdown starting 24 March 2020, with a phased unlock beginning 1 June 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Six cities accounted for around half of reported cases—Mumbai, Delhi, Ahmedabad, Chennai, Pune and Kolkata.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Post-lockdown, the Government of India introduced a contact tracking app called Aarogya Setu to help authorities manage contact tracing and vaccine distribution.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] India's vaccination programme was considered to be the world's largest and most successful with over 90% of citizens getting the first dose and another 65% getting the second dose.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A second wave hit India in April 2021, straining healthcare services.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 21 October 2021, it was reported that the country had surpassed 1 billion vaccinations.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Iran reported its first confirmed cases on 19 February 2020, in Qom.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Early measures included the cancellation/closure of concerts and other cultural events, Friday prayers, and school and university campuses.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Iran became a centre of the pandemic in February 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] More than ten countries had traced their outbreaks to Iran by 28 February, indicating a more severe outbreak than the 388 reported cases.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Iranian Parliament closed, after 23 of its 290 members tested positive on 3 March 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] At least twelve sitting or former Iranian politicians and government officials had died by 17 March 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By August 2021, the pandemic's fifth wave peaked, with more than 400 deaths in 1 day.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] COVID-19 was confirmed in South Korea on 20 January 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Military bases were quarantined after tests showed three infected soldiers.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] South Korea introduced what was then considered the world's largest and best-organised screening programme, isolating infected people, and tracing and quarantining contacts.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Screening methods included mandatory self-reporting by new international arrivals through mobile application, combined with drive-through testing, and increasing testing capability to 20,000 people/day.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite some early criticisms, South Korea's programme was considered a success in controlling the outbreak without quarantining entire cities.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic arrived in Europe with its first confirmed case in Bordeaux, France, on 24 January 2020, and subsequently spread widely across the continent.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 17 March 2020, every country in Europe had confirmed a case, and all had reported at least one death, with the exception of Vatican City.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Italy was the first European nation to experience a major outbreak in early 2020, becoming the first country worldwide to introduce a national lockdown.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 13 March 2020, the WHO declared Europe the epicentre of the pandemic and it remained so until the WHO announced it had been overtaken by South America on 22 May.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 18 March 2020, more than 250 million people were in lockdown in Europe.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite deployment of COVID-19 vaccines, Europe became the pandemic's epicentre once again in late 2021.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Italian outbreak began on 31 January 2020, when two Chinese tourists tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 in Rome.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cases began to rise sharply, which prompted the government to suspend flights to and from China and declare a state of emergency.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 22 February 2020, the Council of Ministers announced a new decree-law to contain the outbreak, which quarantined more than 50,000 people in northern Italy.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 4 March, the Italian government ordered schools and universities closed as Italy reached a hundred deaths.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Sport was suspended completely for at least one month.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 11 March, Italian Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte closed down nearly all commercial activity except supermarkets and pharmacies.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 19 April, the first wave ebbed, as 7-day deaths declined to 433.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 13 October, the Italian government again issued restrictive rules to contain the second wave.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 10 November, Italy surpassed 1 million confirmed infections.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 23 November, it was reported that the second wave of the virus had led some hospitals to stop accepting patients.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The virus was first confirmed to have spread to Spain on 31 January 2020, when a German tourist tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 on La Gomera in the Canary Islands.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Post-hoc genetic analysis has shown that at least 15 strains of the virus had been imported, and community transmission began by mid-February.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 29 March, it was announced that, beginning the following day, all non-essential workers were ordered to remain at home for the next 14 days.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The number of cases increased again in July in a number of cities including Barcelona, Zaragoza and Madrid, which led to reimposition of some restrictions but no national lockdown.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By September 2021, Spain was one of the countries with the highest percentage of its population vaccinated (76% fully vaccinated and 79% with the first dose).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Sweden differed from most other European countries in that it mostly remained open.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Per the Swedish constitution, the Public Health Agency of Sweden has autonomy that prevents political interference and the agency favoured remaining open.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Swedish strategy focused on longer-term measures, based on the assumption that after lockdown the virus would resume spreading, with the same result.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By the end of June, Sweden no longer had excess mortality.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Devolution in the United Kingdom meant that each of its four countries developed its own response.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] England's restrictions were shorter-lived than the others.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The UK government started enforcing social distancing and quarantine measures on 18 March 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 16 March, Prime Minister Boris Johnson advised against non-essential travel and social contact, praising work from home and avoiding venues such as pubs, restaurants, and theatres.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 20 March, the government ordered all leisure establishments to close, and promised to prevent unemployment.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 23 March, Johnson banned gatherings and restricted non-essential travel and outdoor activity.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Unlike previous measures, these restrictions were enforceable by police through fines and dispersal of gatherings.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Most non-essential businesses were ordered to close.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 24 April 2020, it was reported that a promising vaccine trial had begun in England; the government pledged more than £50 million towards research.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 16 April 2020, it was reported that the UK would have first access to the Oxford vaccine, due to a prior contract; should the trial be successful, some 30 million doses would be available.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 2 December 2020, the UK became the first developed country to approve the Pfizer vaccine; 800,000 doses were immediately available for use.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In August 2022 it was reported that viral infection cases had declined in the UK.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The virus arrived in the United States on 13 January 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cases were reported in all North American countries after Saint Kitts and Nevis confirmed a case on 25 March, and in all North American territories after Bonaire confirmed a case on 16 April.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Per *Our World in Data*, 103,436,829 confirmed cases have been reported in the United States with 1,238,189 deaths, the most of any country, and the nineteenth-highest per capita worldwide.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] COVID-19 is the deadliest pandemic in US history; it was the third-leading cause of death in the US in 2020, behind heart disease and cancer.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] From 2019 to 2020, US life expectancy dropped by 3 years for Hispanic Americans, 2.9 years for African Americans, and 1.2 years for white Americans.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] These effects have persisted as US deaths due to COVID-19 in 2021 exceeded those in 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In the United States, COVID-19 vaccines became available under emergency use in December 2020, beginning the national vaccination programme.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The first COVID-19 vaccine was officially approved by the Food and Drug Administration on 23 August 2021.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 18 November 2022, while cases in the U.S. had declined, COVID variants BQ.1/BQ.1.1 had become dominant in the country.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In March 2020, as cases of community transmission were confirmed across Canada, all of its provinces and territories declared states of emergency.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Provinces and territories, to varying degrees, implemented school and daycare closures, prohibitions on gatherings, closures of non-essential businesses and restrictions on entry.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Canada severely restricted its border access, barring travellers from all countries with some exceptions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cases surged across Canada, notably in the provinces of British Columbia, Alberta, Quebec and Ontario, with the formation of the Atlantic Bubble, a travel-restricted area of the country (formed of the four Atlantic provinces).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Vaccine passports were adopted in all provinces and two of the territories.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Per a report on 11 November 2022, Canadian health authorities saw a surge in influenza, while COVID-19 was expected to rise during winter.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have reached South America on 26 February 2020, when Brazil confirmed a case in São Paulo.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 3 April, all countries and territories in South America had recorded at least one case.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 13 May 2020, it was reported that Latin America and the Caribbean had reported over 400,000 cases of COVID-19 infection with 23,091 deaths.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 22 May 2020, citing the rapid increase of infections in Brazil, the WHO declared South America the epicentre of the pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of 16 July 2021, South America had recorded 34,359,631 confirmed cases and 1,047,229 deaths from COVID-19.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Due to a shortage of testing and medical facilities, it is believed that the outbreak is far larger than the official numbers show.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The virus was confirmed to have spread to Brazil on 25 February 2020, when a man from São Paulo who had travelled to Italy tested positive for the virus.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The disease had spread to every federative unit of Brazil by 21 March.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 19 June 2020, the country reported its one millionth case and nearly 49,000 reported deaths.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] One estimate of under-reporting was 22.62% of total reported COVID-19 mortality in 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of 06 June 2026, Brazil, with 38,024,465 confirmed cases and 703,961 deaths, has the third-highest number of confirmed cases and second-highest death toll from COVID-19 in the world, behind only those of the United States and India.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have spread to Africa on 14 February 2020, with the first confirmed case announced in Egypt.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The first confirmed case in sub-Saharan Africa was announced in Nigeria at the end of February 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Within three months, the virus had spread throughout the continent; Lesotho, the last African sovereign state to have remained free of the virus, reported its first case on 13 May 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 26 May, it appeared that most African countries were experiencing community transmission, although testing capacity was limited.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Most of the identified imported cases arrived from Europe and the United States rather than from China where the virus originated.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many preventive measures were implemented by different countries in Africa including travel restrictions, flight cancellations, and event cancellations.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite fears, Africa reported lower death rates than other, more economically developed regions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early June 2021, Africa faced a third wave of COVID infections with cases rising in 14 countries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 4 July the continent recorded more than 251,000 new COVID cases, a 20% increase from the prior week and a 12% increase from the January peak.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] More than sixteen African countries, including Malawi and Senegal, recorded an uptick in new cases.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The WHO labelled it Africa's 'Worst Pandemic Week Ever'.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In October 2022, WHO reported that most countries on the African continent will miss the goal of 70 per cent vaccination by the end of 2022.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have reached Oceania on 25 January 2020, with the first confirmed case reported in Melbourne, Australia.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] It has since spread elsewhere in the region.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Australia and New Zealand were praised for their handling of the pandemic in comparison to other Western nations, with New Zealand and each state in Australia wiping out all community transmission of the virus several times even after re-introduction into the community.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As a result of the high transmissibility of the Delta variant, however, by August 2021, the Australian states of New South Wales and Victoria had conceded defeat in their eradication efforts.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early October 2021, New Zealand also abandoned its elimination strategy.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In November and December, following vaccination efforts, the remaining states of Australia, excluding Western Australia, voluntarily gave up COVID-Zero to open up state and international borders.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The open borders allowed the Omicron variant of COVID-19 to enter quickly, and cases subsequently exceeded 120,000 a day.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By early March 2022, with cases exceeding 1,000 a day, Western Australia conceded defeat in its eradication strategy and opened its borders.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite record cases, Australian jurisdictions slowly removed restrictions such as close contact isolation, mask wearing, and density limits by April 2022.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 9 September 2022, restrictions were significantly relaxed.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The aircraft mask mandate was scrapped nationwide, and daily reporting transitioned to weekly reporting.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 14 September, COVID-19 disaster payment for isolating persons was extended for mandatory isolation.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 22 September, all states had ended mask mandates on public transport, including in Victoria, where the mandate had lasted for approximately 800 days.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 30 September 2022, all Australian leaders declared the emergency response finished and announced the end of isolation requirements.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] These changes were due in part to high levels of 'hybrid immunity' and low case numbers.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Due to its remoteness and sparse population, Antarctica was the last continent to have confirmed cases of COVID-19.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The first cases were reported in December 2020, almost a year after the first cases of COVID-19 were detected in China.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] At least 36 people were infected in the first outbreak in 2020, with several other outbreaks taking place in 2021 and 2022.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNSC) was criticised for its slow response, especially regarding the UN's global ceasefire, which aimed to open up humanitarian access to conflict zones.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The United Nations Security Council was criticised due to the inadequate manner in which it dealt with the COVID-19 pandemic, namely the poor ability to create international collaboration during this crisis.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 23 March 2020, United Nations Secretary-General António Manuel de Oliveira Guterres appealed for a global ceasefire; 172 UN member states and observers signed a non-binding supporting statement in June, and the UN Security Council passed a resolution supporting it in July.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 29 September 2020, Guterres urged the International Monetary Fund to help certain countries via debt relief and also call for countries to increase contributions to develop vaccines.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The WHO spearheaded initiatives such as the COVID-19 Solidarity Response Fund to raise money for the pandemic response, the UN COVID-19 Supply Chain Task Force, and the solidarity trial for investigating potential treatment options for the disease.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVAX programme, co-led by the WHO, GAVI, and the Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations (CEPI), aimed to accelerate the development, manufacture, and distribution of COVID-19 vaccines, and to guarantee fair and equitable access across the world.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic shook the world's economy, with especially severe economic damage in the United States, Europe and Latin America.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A consensus report by American intelligence agencies in April 2021 concluded, "Efforts to contain and manage the virus have reinforced nationalist trends globally, as some states turned inward to protect their citizens and sometimes cast blame on marginalised groups".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] COVID-19 inflamed partisanship and polarisation around the world as bitter arguments exploded over how to respond.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] International trade was disrupted amid the formation of no-entry enclaves.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic led many countries and regions to impose quarantines, entry bans, or other restrictions, either for citizens, recent travellers to affected areas, or for all travellers.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Travel collapsed worldwide, damaging the travel sector.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The effectiveness of travel restrictions was questioned as the virus spread across the world.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] One study found that travel restrictions only modestly affected the initial spread, unless combined with other infection prevention and control measures.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Researchers concluded that "travel restrictions are most useful in the early and late phase of an epidemic" and "restrictions of travel from Wuhan unfortunately came too late".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The European Union rejected the idea of suspending the Schengen free travel zone.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Several countries repatriated their citizens and diplomatic staff from Wuhan and surrounding areas, primarily through charter flights.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Canada, the United States, Japan, India, Sri Lanka, Australia, France, Argentina, Germany and Thailand were among the first to do so.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Brazil and New Zealand evacuated their own nationals and others.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 14 March, South Africa repatriated 112 South Africans who tested negative, while four who showed symptoms were left behind.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Pakistan declined to evacuate its citizens.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 15 February, the US announced it would evacuate Americans aboard the *Diamond Princess* cruise ship, and on 21 February, Canada evacuated 129 Canadians from the ship.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early March, the Indian government began repatriating its citizens from Iran.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 20 March, the United States began to withdraw some troops from Iraq.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic and responses to it damaged the global economy.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 27 February 2020, worries about the outbreak crushed US stock indexes, which posted their sharpest falls since 2008.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Tourism collapsed due to travel restrictions, closing of public places including travel attractions, and advice of governments against travel.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Airlines cancelled flights, while British regional airline Flybe collapsed.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The cruise line industry was hard hit, and train stations and ferry ports closed.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] International mail stopped or was delayed.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The retail sector faced reductions in store hours or closures.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Retailers in Europe and Latin America faced traffic declines of 40 per cent.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] North America and Middle East retailers saw a 50–60 per cent drop.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Shopping centres faced a 33–43 per cent drop in foot traffic in March compared to February.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Mall operators around the world coped by increasing sanitation, installing thermal scanners to check the temperature of shoppers, and cancelling events.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Hundreds of millions of jobs were lost, including more than 40 million jobs in the US.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to a report by Yelp, about 60% of US businesses that closed will stay shut permanently.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The International Labour Organization (ILO) reported that the income generated in the first nine months of 2020 from work across the world dropped by 10.7%, or $3.5 trillion.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Pandemic fears led to panic buying, emptying groceries of essentials such as food, toilet paper, and bottled water.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Panic buying stemmed from perceived threat, perceived scarcity, fear of the unknown, coping behaviour and social psychological factors (e.g. social influence and trust).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Supply shortages were due to disruption to factory and logistic operations; shortages were worsened by supply chain disruptions from factory and port shutdowns, and labour shortages.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Shortages continued as managers underestimated the speed of economic recovery after the initial economic crash.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The technology industry, in particular, warned of delays from underestimates of semiconductor demand for vehicles and other products.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to WHO Secretary-General Tedros Ghebreyesus, demand for personal protective equipment (PPE) rose one hundredfold, pushing prices up twentyfold.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In September 2021, the World Bank reported that food prices remained generally stable and the supply outlook remained positive.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] However, the poorest countries witnessed a sharp increase in food prices, reaching the highest level since the pandemic began.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Agricultural Commodity Price Index stabilised in the third quarter but remained 17% higher than in January 2021.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By contrast, petroleum products were in surplus at the beginning of the pandemic, as demand for gasoline and other products collapsed due to reduced commuting and other trips.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The 2021 global energy crisis was driven by a global surge in demand as the world economy recovered.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Energy demand was particularly strong in Asia.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The performing arts and cultural heritage sectors were profoundly affected by the pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Both organisations' and individuals' operations have been impacted globally.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By March 2020, across the world and to varying degrees, museums, libraries, performance venues, and other cultural institutions had been indefinitely closed with their exhibitions, events and performances cancelled or postponed.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A 2021 UNESCO report estimated ten million job losses worldwide in the culture and creative industries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some services continued through digital platforms, such as live streaming concerts or web-based arts festivals.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic affected political systems, causing suspensions of legislative activities, isolations or deaths of politicians, and rescheduled elections.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Although they developed broad support among epidemiologists, NPIs (non-pharmaceutical interventions) were controversial in many countries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Intellectual opposition came primarily from other fields, along with heterodox epidemiologists.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic (and the response of Brazilian politicians to it) led to widespread panic, confusion, and pessimism in Brazil.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] When questioned regarding record deaths in the country in April 2020, Brazilian president Jair Bolsonaro said "So what?
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A series of federal health ministers resigned or were dismissed after they refused to implement Bolsonaro's policies.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Disagreements between federal and state governments led to a chaotic and delayed response to the rapid spread of the virus, exacerbated by preexisting social and economic disparities in the country.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Employment, investment and valuation of the Brazilian real plummeted to record lows.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Brazil was also heavily affected by the Delta and Omicron variants.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] At the height of the outbreak in the spring of 2021, 3,000+ Brazilians were dying per day.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Bolsonaro's loss to Lula da Silva in the 2022 presidential election is widely credited to the former's mishandling of the pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Multiple provincial-level administrators of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) were dismissed over their handling of quarantine measures.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some commentators claimed this move was intended to protect CCP General Secretary Xi Jinping.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The US intelligence community claimed that China intentionally under-reported its COVID-19 caseload.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Chinese government maintained that it acted swiftly and transparently.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Journalists and activists in China who reported on the pandemic were detained by authorities, including Zhang Zhan, who was arrested and tortured.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early March 2020, the Italian government criticised the EU's lack of solidarity with Italy.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 22 March 2020, after a phone call with Italian Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte, Russian president Vladimir Putin ordered the Russian army to send military medics, disinfection vehicles, and other medical equipment to Italy.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In early April, Norway and EU states like Romania and Austria started to offer help by sending medical personnel and disinfectant, and European Commission president Ursula von der Leyen offered an official apology to the country.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Beginning in mid-April 2020, protestors objected to government-imposed business closures and restrictions on personal movement and assembly.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Simultaneously, essential workers protested unsafe conditions and low wages by participating in a brief general strike.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some political analysts claimed that the pandemic contributed to US President Donald Trump's 2020 defeat to former Vice President Joe Biden and Senator Kamala Harris.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic in the United States prompted calls for the United States to adopt social policies common in other wealthy countries, including universal health care, universal child care, paid sick leave, and higher levels of funding for public health.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Kaiser Family Foundation estimated that preventable hospitalisations of unvaccinated Americans in the second half of 2021 cost US$13.8 billion.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] There were also protest in regards to vaccine mandates in the United States.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In January 2022, the US Supreme Court struck down an OSHA rule that mandated vaccination or a testing regimen for all companies with greater than 100 employees.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The number of journalists imprisoned or detained increased worldwide; some detentions were related to the pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The planned NATO "Defender 2020" military exercise in Germany, Poland and the Baltic states, the largest NATO war exercise since the end of the Cold War, was held on a reduced scale.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Iranian government was heavily affected by the virus, which infected some two dozen parliament members and political figures.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Iranian president Hassan Rouhani wrote a public letter to world leaders asking for help on 14 March 2020, due to a lack of access to international markets.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Saudi Arabia, which had launched a military intervention in Yemen in March 2015, declared a ceasefire.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Diplomatic relations between Japan and South Korea worsened.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] South Korea criticised Japan's "ambiguous and passive quarantine efforts" after Japan announced travellers from South Korea must quarantine for two weeks.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] South Korean society was initially polarised on president Moon Jae-in's response to the crisis; many Koreans signed petitions calling for Moon's impeachment or praising his response.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some countries passed emergency legislation.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some commentators expressed concern that it could allow governments to strengthen their grip on power.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In Hungary, the parliament voted to allow Prime Minister Viktor Orbán to rule by decree indefinitely, suspend parliament and elections, and punish those deemed to have spread false information.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In countries such as Egypt, Turkey, and Thailand, opposition activists and government critics were arrested for allegedly spreading fake news.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In India, journalists criticising the government's response were arrested or issued warnings by police and authorities.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic disrupted food systems worldwide, hitting at a time when hunger and undernourishment were rising- an estimated 690 million people lacked food security in 2019.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Food access fell – driven by falling incomes, lost remittances, and disruptions to food production.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic and its accompanying lockdowns and travel restrictions slowed movement of food aid.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to the WHO, 811 million people were undernourished in 2020, "likely related to the fallout of COVID-19".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic impacted educational systems in many countries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many governments temporarily closed educational institutions, often replaced by online education.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Other countries, such as Sweden, kept their schools open.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of September 2020, approximately 1.077 billion learners were affected due to school closures.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] School closures impacted students, teachers, and families with far-reaching economic and societal consequences.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] They shed light on social and economic issues, including student debt, digital learning, food insecurity, and homelessness, as well as access to childcare, health care, housing, internet, and disability services.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The impact was more severe for disadvantaged children.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many countries, including Bangladesh, granted auto promotion to the public examination candidates.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The Higher Education Policy Institute reported that around 63% of students claimed worsened mental health as a result of the pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic impacted global health for many conditions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Visits for heart attack symptoms declined by 38% in the US and 40% in Spain.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The head of cardiology at the University of Arizona said, "My worry is some of these people are dying at home because they're too scared to go to the hospital".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] People with strokes and appendicitis were less likely to seek treatment.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Medical supply shortages impacted many people.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic impacted mental health, increasing anxiety, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder, affecting healthcare workers, patients and quarantined individuals.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In late 2022, during the first northern hemisphere autumn and winter seasons following the widespread relaxation of global public health measures, North America and Europe experienced a surge in respiratory viruses and coinfections in both adults and children.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This formed the beginning of the 2022–2023 paediatric care crisis and what some experts termed a "tripledemic" of seasonal influenza, respiratory syncytial virus (RSV), and SARS-CoV-2 throughout North America.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In the United Kingdom, paediatric infections also began to spike beyond pre-pandemic levels, albeit with different illnesses, such as Group A streptococcal infection and resultant scarlet fever.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of mid-December 2022, 19 children in the UK had died due to Strep A and the wave of infections had begun to spread into North America and Mainland Europe.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The B/Yamagata lineage of influenza B might have become extinct in 2020/2021 due to COVID-19 pandemic measures.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] There have been no naturally occurring cases confirmed since March 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In 2023, the WHO concluded that protection against the Yamagata lineage was no longer necessary in the seasonal flu vaccine, reducing the number of lineages targeted by the vaccine from four to three.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Preventative measures taken during the COVID-19 pandemic may have impacted the number of bronchiolitis cases, with observed decreases in cases during the pandemic followed by an increase when preventative measures were rolled back.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic and the reaction to it positively affected the environment and climate as a result of reduced human activity.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] During the "anthropause", fossil fuel use decreased, resource consumption declined, and waste disposal improved, generating less pollution.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Planned air travel and vehicle transportation declined.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In China, lockdowns and other measures resulted in a 26% decrease in coal consumption, and a 50% reduction in nitrogen oxides emissions.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In 2020, a worldwide study on mammalian wildlife responses to human presence during COVID lockdowns found complex patterns of animal behaviour.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Carnivores were generally less active when humans were around, while herbivores in developed areas were more active.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Among other findings, this suggested that herbivores may view humans as a shield against predators, highlighting the importance of location and human presence history in understanding wildlife responses to changes in human activity in a given area.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A wide variety of largely mammalian species, both captive and wild, have been shown to be susceptible to SARS-CoV-2, with some encountering a particularly high degree of fatal outcomes.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In particular, both farmed and wild mink have developed highly symptomatic and severe COVID-19 infections, with a mortality rate as high as 35–55% according to one study.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] White-tailed deer, on the other hand, have largely avoided severe outcomes but have effectively become natural reservoirs of the virus, with large numbers of free-ranging deer infected throughout the US and Canada, including approximately 80% of Iowa's wild deer herd.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] An August 2023 study appeared to confirm the status of white-tailed deer as a disease reservoir, noting that the viral evolution of SARS-CoV-2 in deer occurs at triple the rate of its evolution in humans and that infection rates remained high, even in areas rarely frequented by humans.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Heightened prejudice, xenophobia, and racism toward people of Chinese and East Asian descent were documented around the world.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Reports from February 2020, when most confirmed cases were confined to China, cited racist sentiments about Chinese people 'deserving' the virus.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Individuals of Asian descent in Europe and North America reported increasing instances of racially motivated abuse and assaults as a result of the pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] US president Donald Trump was criticised for referring to SARS-CoV-2 as the "Chinese Virus" and "Kung Flu", terms which were condemned as being racist and xenophobic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Age-based discrimination against older adults increased during the pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This was attributed to their perceived vulnerability and subsequent physical and social isolation measures, which, coupled with their reduced social activity, increased dependency on others.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Similarly, limited digital literacy left the elderly more vulnerable to isolation, depression, and loneliness.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] American bioethicist Arthur Caplan responded to Kampf, writing "Criticising [the unvaccinated] who... wind up in hospitals and morgues in huge numbers, put stress on finite resources, and prolong the pandemic... is not stigmatising, it is deserved moral condemnation".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In January 2022, Amnesty International urged Italy to change their anti-COVID-19 restrictions to avoid discrimination against unvaccinated people, saying that "the government must continue to ensure that the entire population can enjoy its fundamental rights".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The restrictions included mandatory vaccination over the age of 50, and mandatory vaccination to use public transport.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic triggered massive changes in behaviour, from increased Internet commerce to cultural changes in the workplace.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Online retailers in the US posted $791.70 billion in sales in 2020, an increase of 32.4% from $598.02 billion the year before.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Home delivery orders increased, while indoor restaurant dining shut down due to lockdown orders or low sales.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Hackers, cybercriminals and scammers took advantage of the changes to launch new online attacks.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Education in some countries temporarily shifted from physical attendance to video conferencing.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Massive layoffs shrank the airline, travel, hospitality, and other industries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite most corporations implementing measures to address COVID-19 in the workplace, a poll from Catalyst found that as many as 68% of employees around the world felt that these policies were only performative and "not genuine".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic led to a surge in remote work.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to a Gallup poll, only 4% of US employees were fully remote before the pandemic, compared to 43% in May 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Among white collar workers, that shift was more pronounced, with 6% increasing to 65% in the same period.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] That trend continued in later stages of the pandemic, with many workers choosing to remain remote even after workplaces reopened.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many Nordic, European, and Asian companies increased their recruitment of international remote workers even as the pandemic waned, partially to save on labour costs.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This also led to a talent drain in the global south and in remote areas in the global north.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] High cost of living and dense urban areas also lost office real estate value due to remote worker exodus.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By May 2023, due to increasing layoffs and concerns over productivity, some white collar workplaces in the US had resorted to performance review penalties and indirect incentives (e.g. donations to charity) to encourage workers to return to the office.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A 2021 study noted that the COVID-19 pandemic had increased interest in epidemics and infectious diseases among both historians and the general public.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Prior to the pandemic, these topics were usually overlooked by "general" history and only received attention in the history of medicine.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many comparisons were made between the COVID-19 and 1918 influenza pandemics, including the development of anti-mask movements, the widespread promotion of misinformation and the impact of socioeconomic disparities.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In some areas, religious groups exacerbated the spread of the virus, through large gatherings and the dissemination of misinformation.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some religious leaders decried what they saw as violations of religious freedom.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In other cases, religious identity was a beneficial factor for health, increasing compliance with public health measures and protecting against the negative effects of isolation on mental wellbeing.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some news organisations removed their online paywalls for some or all of their pandemic-related articles and posts.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many scientific publishers provided pandemic-related journal articles to the public free of charge as part of the National Institutes of Health's COVID-19 Public Health Emergency Initiative.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] According to one estimate from researchers at the University of Rome, 89.5% of COVID-19-related papers were open access, compared to an average of 48.8% for the ten most deadly human diseases.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The share of papers published on preprint servers prior to peer review increased dramatically.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] During the pandemic, Web GIS technology was leveraged to provide up to date visualisations of data related to the pandemic with the public.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Employing this technology, the Johns Hopkins University COVID-19 dashboard served as the first global visualisation of COVID-19 data, which established it as the default method for government agencies to dissemeniate relevant spatial information.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] These dashboards were described by Jonathan Everts as "the most striking cultural artefact of the current coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2) pandemic", and during the pandemic every state government in the United States maintained one.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Misinformation and conspiracy theories about the pandemic have been widespread; they travel through mass media, social media and text messaging.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In March 2020, WHO declared an "infodemic" of incorrect information.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cognitive biases, such as confirmation bias, are linked to conspiracy beliefs, including COVID-19 vaccine hesitancy.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic had a major impact on popular culture.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] It was included in the narratives of ongoing pre-pandemic television series and become a central narrative in new ones, with mixed results.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Writing for *The New York Times* about the then-upcoming BBC sitcom *Pandemonium* on 16 December 2020, David Segal asked, "Are we ready to laugh about Covid-19?
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Or rather, is there anything amusing, or recognizable in a humorous way, about life during a plague, with all of its indignities and setbacks, not to mention its rituals and rules".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The pandemic had driven some people to seek peaceful escapism in media, while others were drawn towards fictional pandemics (e.g. zombie apocalypses) as an alternate form of escapism.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Common themes have included contagion, isolation and loss of control.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Many drew comparisons to the fictional film *Contagion* (2011), praising its accuracies while noting some differences, such as the lack of an orderly vaccine rollout.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As people turned to music to relieve emotions evoked by the pandemic, Spotify listenership showed that classical, ambient and children's genres grew, while pop, country and dance remained relatively stable.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A March 2022 review declared a transition to endemic status to be "inevitable".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In June 2022, an article in *Human Genomics* said that the pandemic was still "raging", but that "now is the time to explore the transition from the pandemic to the endemic phase".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Another review that month predicted that the virus that causes COVID-19 would become the fifth endemic seasonal coronavirus, alongside four other human coronaviruses.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] A February 2023 review of the four common cold coronaviruses concluded that the virus would become seasonal and, like the common cold, cause less severe disease for most people.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Another 2023 review stated that the transition to endemic COVID-19 may take years or decades.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] On 5 May 2023, the WHO declared that the pandemic was no longer a public health emergency of international concern.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This led several media outlets to incorrectly report that this meant the pandemic was "over".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The WHO commented to Full Fact that it was unlikely to declare the pandemic over "in the near future" and mentioned cholera, which it considers to have been a pandemic since 1961 (i.e., continuously for the last 65 years).
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] The WHO does not have an official category for pandemics or make declarations of when pandemics start or end.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In June 2023, Hans Kluge, director of the WHO in Europe, commented that "While the international public health emergency may have ended, the pandemic certainly has not".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Epidemics and pandemics usually end when the disease becomes endemic, and when the disease becomes "an accepted, manageable part of normal life in a given society".
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] As of March 2024, there was no widely agreed definition of when a disease is or is not a pandemic, though efforts at a formal definition were underway.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Experts asked by *Time* that month noted that COVID-19 continued to circulate and cause disease, but expressed uncertainty as to whether it should still be described as a pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In December 2024, Director-General of the World Health Organization Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus stated that COVID should not be referred to in past tense as it is "still with us, still causes acute disease and Long COVID and still kills...
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] By 2025, five years after the start of the pandemic, experts asked by *The Independent* and *The Washington Post* generally considered COVID-19 to have become endemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Cases and deaths from COVID-19 still remained high; in the United States, the only two infectious diseases causing more than 10,000 deaths a year were flu and COVID, according to an expert in *The Washington Post*.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Despite strong economic rebounds following the initial lockdowns in early 2020, towards the latter phases of the pandemic, many countries began to experience long-term economic effects.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Several countries saw high inflation rates which had global impacts, particularly in developing countries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some economic impacts such as supply chain and trade operations were seen as more permanent as the pandemic exposed major weaknesses in these systems.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] In Australia, the pandemic caused an increase in occupational burnout in 2022.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] During the pandemic, a large percentage of workers in Canada came to prefer working from home, which had an impact on the traditional work model.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some corporations made efforts to force workers to return to work on-site, while some embraced the idea.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] There was a "travel boom" causing air travel to recover at rates faster than anticipated, and the aviation industry became profitable in 2023 for the first time since 2019, before the pandemic.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] However, economic issues meant some predicted that the boom would begin to slow down.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Business travel on airlines was still below pre-pandemic levels and is predicted not to recover.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] An increase in excess deaths from underlying causes not related to COVID-19 has been largely blamed on systematic issues causing delays in health care and screening during the pandemic, which has resulted in an increase of non-COVID-19 related deaths.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] During the pandemic, millions of children missed out on vaccinations as countries focused efforts on combating COVID-19.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Efforts were made to increase vaccination rates among children in low-income countries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] These efforts were successful in increasing vaccination rates for some diseases, though the UN noted that post-pandemic measles vaccinations were still falling behind.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Some of the decrease in immunisation was driven by an increase in mistrust of public health officials.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] This was seen in both low-income and high-income countries.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Several African countries saw a decline in vaccinations due to misinformation around the pandemic flowing into other areas.
[src:aloha-festivals/covid-19-pandemic-p02] Immunisation rates have yet to recover in the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The term is often used in connection with issues related to the protection of Indigenous intellectual property.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The deliberate action of keeping cultural heritage for future generations is known as preservation in American English or conservation in British English.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] This concept is promoted by cultural and historical ethnic museums and cultural centers, though these terms may have more specific or technical meanings in the same contexts in the other dialect.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Preserved heritage has become an anchor of the global tourism industry, a major contributor of economic value to local communities.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Legal protection of cultural property comprises a number of international agreements and national laws.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] United Nations, UNESCO, and Blue Shield International are involved in the protection of cultural heritage.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] This also applies to the integration of United Nations peacekeeping.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Cultural property includes the physical, or "tangible" cultural heritage, such as artworks.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] These are generally split into two groups of movable and immovable heritage.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Immovable heritage includes buildings (which themselves may include installed art such as organs, stained glass windows, and frescos), large industrial installations, residential projects, or other historic places and monuments.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Moveable heritage includes books, documents, moveable artworks, machines, clothing, and other artifacts, that are considered worthy of preservation for the future.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] These include objects significant to the archaeology, architecture, science, or technology of a specified culture.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] "Intangible cultural heritage" consists of non-physical aspects of a particular culture, more often maintained by social customs during a specific period in history.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The concept includes the ways and means of behavior in a society and the often formal rules for operating in a particular cultural climate.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] These include social values and traditions, customs and practices, aesthetic and spiritual beliefs, artistic expression, language and other aspects of human activity.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The significance of physical artifacts can be interpreted as an act against the backdrop of socioeconomic, political, ethnic, religious, and philosophical values of a particular group of people.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Naturally, intangible cultural heritage is more difficult to preserve than physical objects.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] These kinds of heritage sites often serve as an important component in a country's tourist industry, attracting many visitors from abroad as well as locally.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Heritage can also include cultural landscapes (natural features that may have cultural attributes).
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Digital heritage is made up of computer-based materials such as texts, databases, images, sounds and software being retained for future generations.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Digital heritage includes physical objects such as documents which have been digitized for retention and artifacts which are "born digital", i.e. originally created digitally and having no physical form.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Digital heritage also encompasses visual identity records, including the preservation of brand trademarks and logo evolution.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] These elements contribute to cultural memory by documenting how visual symbols change over time and how they reflect social, commercial and technological development.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Such archives help illustrate historical continuity in branding, providing reference points for researchers and design historians.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] A recent study used high‑resolution photogrammetry and 3D scanning to analyse Graeco‑Roman funerary masks, showing how digital methods can help reconstruct and document fragmented cultural artefacts.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] There have been examples of respect for the cultural assets of enemies since ancient times.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The roots of today's legal situation for the precise protection of cultural heritage also lie in some of the regulations of Austria's ruler Maria Theresa (1717 - 1780) and the demands of the Congress of Vienna (1814/15) not to remove works of art from their place of origin in the war.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The 1863 Lieber code, a military legal code governing the wartime conduct of the Union Army also set rules for the protection of cultural heritage.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The process continued at the end of the 19th century when, in 1874 (in Brussels), at least a draft international agreement on the laws and customs of war was agreed.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] 25 years later, in 1899, an international peace conference was held in the Netherlands on the initiative of Tsar Nicholas II of Russia, with the aim of revising the declaration (which was never ratified) and adopting a convention.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907 also significantly advanced international law and laid down the principle of the immunity of cultural property.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Three decades later, in 1935, the preamble to the Treaty on the Protection of Artistic and Scientific Institutions (Roerich Pact) was formulated.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] On the initiative of UNESCO, the Hague Convention for the Protection of Cultural Property in the Event of Armed Conflict was signed in 1954.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Protection of cultural heritage or protection of cultural goods refers to all measures aimed at protecting cultural property against damage, destruction, theft, embezzlement, or other loss.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The term "monument protection" is also used for immovable cultural property.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Legal protection of cultural heritage comprises a number of international agreements and national laws.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] There is a close partnership between the UN, United Nations peacekeeping, UNESCO, the International Committee of the Red Cross and Blue Shield International.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The protection of cultural heritage should also preserve the particularly sensitive cultural memory, the growing cultural diversity, and the economic basis of a state, a municipality, or a region.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Whereby there is also a connection between cultural user disruption or cultural heritage and the cause of flight.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] But only through fundamental cooperation, including the military units and the planning staff, with the locals can the protection of world heritage sites, archaeological finds, exhibits, and archaeological sites from destruction, looting, and robbery be implemented sustainably.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The founding president of Blue Shield International Karl von Habsburg summed it up with the words: "Without the local community and without the local participants, that would be completely impossible".
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Objects are a part of the study of human history because they provide a concrete basis for ideas, and can validate them.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Their preservation demonstrates a recognition of the necessity of the past and of the things that tell its story.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] In *The Past is a Foreign Country*, David Lowenthal observes that preserved objects also validate memories.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] This poses a danger as places and things are damaged by the hands of tourists, the light required to display them, and other risks of making an object known and available.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The reality of this risk reinforces the fact that all artifacts are in a constant state of chemical transformation so that what is considered to be preserved is actually changing – it is never as it once was.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Similarly changing is the value each generation may place on the past and on the artifacts that link it to the past.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Cultural heritage is addressed not only through preservation and conservation practices, but also through policy, governance, and Cultural Planning frameworks at the municipal and regional level.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Classical civilizations, especially Indian, have attributed supreme importance to the preservation of tradition.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Its central idea was that social institutions, scientific knowledge, and technological applications need to use a "heritage" as a "resource".
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Ethics considered that what had been inherited should not be consumed, but should be handed over, possibly enriched, to successive generations.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] This was a moral imperative for all, except in the final life stage of sannyasa.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] What one generation considers "cultural heritage" may be rejected by the next generation, only to be revived by a subsequent generation.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Recent research based on communities in Bradford has explored the importance of identity and the role of heritage and culture for wellbeing, community cohesion and resilience.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The Convention Concerning the Protection of World Cultural and Natural Heritage was adopted by the General Conference of UNESCO in 1972.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] As of 2011, there are 936 World Heritage Sites: 725 cultural, 183 natural, and 28 mixed properties, in 153 countries.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Each of these sites is considered important to the international community.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Underwater cultural heritage is protected by the UNESCO Convention on the Protection of the Underwater Cultural Heritage.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] In addition, UNESCO has begun designating masterpieces of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The Committee on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights sitting as part of the United Nations Economic and Social Council with article 15 of its Covenant had sought to instill the principles under which cultural heritage is protected as part of a basic human right.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Government Accountability Office issued a report describing some of the United States' cultural property protection efforts.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] In the last decades some of the most important heritage scholars have created the open heritage movement.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Much of heritage preservation work is done at the national, regional, or local levels of society.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Ancient archaeological artefacts and archaeological sites are naturally prone to damage due to their age and environmental conditions.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Also, there have been tragic occurrences of unexpected human-made disasters, such as in the cases of a fire that took place in the 200 years old National Museum of Brazil and the UNESCO World Heritage Site of the Notre Dame Cathedral in Paris.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Therefore, there is a growing need to digitize cultural heritage in order to preserve them in the face of potential calamities such as climate change, natural disaster, poor policy or inadequate infrastructure.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] For example, the Library of Congress has started to digitize its collections in a special program called the National Digital Library Program.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The Smithsonian has also been actively digitizing its collection with the release of the "Smithsonian X 3D Explorer," allowing anyone to engage with the digitized versions of the museum's millions of artifacts, of which only two percent are on display.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] 3D scanning devices used for heritage preservation produce a high-precision digital reference model that not only digitizes condition but also provides a 3D virtual model for replication.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] The high cost and relative complexity of 3D scanning technologies made it quite impractical in the past, but technology advances and lower relative costs have made even mobile based scanning applications able to create a virtual museum.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] There is still a low level of digital archiving of archaeological data obtained via excavation, even in the UK where the lead digital archive for archaeology, the Archaeology Data Service, was established in the 1990s.
[src:aloha-festivals/cultural-heritage] Across the globe, countries are at different stages of dealing with digital archaeological archives, all dealing with differences in statutory requirements, and legal ownership of archives and infrastructure.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] A **hālau hula** (Hawaiian pronunciation: [haːˈlɐw ˈhulə]) is a school or hall in which the Hawaiian dance form called hula is taught.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The term comes from *hālau,* literally, "long house, as for canoes or hula instruction"; "meeting house", and *hula,* a Polynesian dance form of the Hawaiian Islands.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Today, a *hālau hula* is commonly known as a school or formal institution for hula where the primary responsibility of the people within the *hālau* is to perpetuate the cultural practice of hula.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Some focus primarily on ancient styles of hula, others on modern styles, and some study both.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Some hālau continue to preserve very strict *kapu*, sacred protocols, while others are *noa*, or free of kapu.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The styles of hula taught in different hālau also can vary greatly.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Styles are passed down from kumu to *haumāna*, and knowledgeable students of hula can tell which hula lineage is represented by watching the dancer's presentation.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Traditionally, a hālau was constructed as a sacred space and dedicated to the god Laka.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Although Hawaiians had many gods, within a hālau Laka was important as evidenced by the *kuahu,* or altar, which stood in the hālau space and required constant care.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The kuahu was adorned with greenery in honor of the Gods, song-offerings and *pule*, or prayers*,* were also offered to this sacred dwelling space within the hālau.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The location of hālau today vary widely, from the kumu's home to community centers, to the lawns of parks.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Hālau hula can be found wherever there is space and a company or troupe of hula students.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The internal structure of a hālau hula can vary quite a bit, generally these are led by a *kumu hula*, or master teacher, whose position is roughly equivalent to that of a headmaster.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The kumu is responsible for maintaining the integrity of the style and traditions handed down to them by their kumu, during their hula training.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Their *kuleana*, or responsibility, is therefore to uphold the training and discipline of their haumāna through a perpetuation of their hālau traditions.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The kumu is also responsible for the spiritual integrity of the hālau, and is responsible for instructing students in the proper care and protocol of the hālau, which includes their physical well-being by teaching good exercise, dietary, and hygienic practices.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Within a hālau there are typically two classes of performers.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The *ʻōlapa,* or dancers, who, like the ʻōlapa tree (*Cheirodendron trigynum*) dance with agility and bend gracefully alikened to the motion of the leaves of the ʻōlapa.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Along with the *hoʻopaʻa*, or steadfast class of performers.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The hoʻopaʻa are responsible for instrumentation and typically chant and dance with their instruments while sitting or kneeling, accompanying the ʻōlapa dancers.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Typically, this role was for students with more experience and maturity.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The *poʻopuaʻa*, or head student, is often the kumu's protégé, and under the direction of the kumu oversees the protocol and rituals of the hālau.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] The *alakaʻi* or "guides" act as teaching assistants, with the more advanced effectively being student teachers.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Alakaʻi often will assist less experienced *haumāna* with their lessons, and coach them with the more difficult steps and moves.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Prior to European contact, the Hawaiian language had no word for "school", as the concept of a specialized place of instruction did not exist in Hawai`i prior to the arrival of Christian missionaries.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] In ancient times, students joining a hālau hula would be dedicated solely to the study of hula for the duration of their training.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Their families would provide maintenance for the support of the hālau.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Hālau hula training was strict, with haumāna put on *kapu* or rules and codes of conduct which banned the cutting of hair and the practicing of any kind of sexual activity.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Today, students have set hours for study at the hālau, and often pay monthly dues to help the kumu with support and maintenance.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Present-day hālau hula each have their own set of rules for their haumāna, with many still enforcing the traditional rule of not cutting one's hair.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Each year, the distinctive styles of each hālau can be seen at the Merrie Monarch Festival held in Hilo.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Aloha Hula) and group performances in categories for kāne (men) and wāhine (women).
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Winners are recognized for their performances of kahiko (traditional), ʻauana (contemporary) and an Overall Festival Winner is recognized.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] Four basic steps are commonly used in all hālau hula, and each of the steps has many variants.
[src:aloha-festivals/halau-hula] All of the basic steps in hula require the shoulders to remain steady and both knees to be in a bent position at all times.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii consists of 137 volcanic islands that make up almost the entire Hawaiian archipelago (the exception is Midway Atoll).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Spanning 1,500 miles (2,400 km), the state is physiographically and ethnologically part of the Polynesian subregion of Oceania.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii's ocean coastline is consequently the fourth-longest in the U.S., at about 750 miles (1,210 km).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The eight main islands, from northwest to southeast, are Niʻihau, Kauaʻi, Oʻahu, Molokaʻi, Lānaʻi, Kahoʻolawe, Maui, and Hawaiʻi, after which the state is named; the last is often called the "Big Island" or "Hawaiʻi Island" to avoid confusion with the state or archipelago.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The uninhabited Northwestern Hawaiian Islands make up most of the Papahānaumokuākea Marine National Monument, the largest protected area in the U.S. and the fourth-largest in the world.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Of the 50 U.S. states, Hawaii is the eighth-smallest in land area and the 11th-least populous; but with 1.4 million residents, it ranks 13th in population density.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Two-thirds of Hawaii residents live on Oʻahu, home to the state's capital and largest city, Honolulu.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii is one of the most demographically diverse U.S. states, owing to its location in the central Pacific and over two centuries of migration.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] As one of nine majority-minority states, it has the only Asian American plurality, the largest Buddhist community, and largest proportion of multiracial people in the U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Consequently, Hawaii is a unique melting pot of North American and East Asian cultures, in addition to its indigenous Hawaiian heritage.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Settled by Polynesians sometime between 1000 and 1200 CE, Hawaii was home to numerous independent chiefdoms.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1778, British explorer James Cook was the first known non-Polynesian to arrive at the archipelago; early British influence is reflected in the state flag, which bears a Union Jack.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii became a unified, internationally recognized kingdom in 1810, remaining independent until American and European businessmen overthrew the monarchy in 1893; this led to annexation by the U.S. in 1898.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] As a strategically valuable U.S. territory, Hawaii was attacked by Japan on December 7, 1941, which brought it global and historical significance, and contributed to America's entry into World War II.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii is the most recent state to join the union, on August 21, 1959.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1993, the U.S. government formally apologized for its role in the overthrow of Hawaii's government, which had spurred the Hawaiian sovereignty movement and has led to ongoing efforts to obtain redress for the indigenous population.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] From the late 19th century until the mid-20th century, Hawaii's economy was dominated by a plantation economy, it remains a major agricultural exporter due to its fertile soil and uniquely tropical climate in the U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Its economy has gradually diversified since the mid-20th century, with tourism and military defense becoming the two largest sectors.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The state attracts visitors, surfers, and scientists with its diverse natural scenery, tropical climate, abundant public beaches, oceanic surroundings, active volcanoes, and clear skies.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] However, since the onset of the 21st century, climate change has wrought existential threats upon Hawaii and its tourism economy, featuring increasing drought and water shortages, sea level rise and hotel flooding in Downtown Honolulu, and wildfire threats.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] These factors are compounded by an aging and declining population, with an exodus emigrating to the U.S. mainland.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Pacific Fleet, the world's largest naval command, as well as 75,000 employees of the Defense Department.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii's isolation results in one of the highest costs of living in the U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] However, Hawaii is the third-wealthiest state, and residents have the longest life expectancy of any U.S. state, at 80.7 years.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The State of Hawaii derives its name from the name of its largest island, Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] A common explanation of the name of Hawaiʻi is that it was named for Hawaiʻiloa, a figure from Hawaiian oral tradition.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] He is said to have discovered the islands when they were first settled.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Hawaiian language word *Hawaiʻi* is very similar to Proto-Polynesian **Sawaiki*, with the reconstructed meaning 'homeland'.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Cognates of *Hawaiʻi* are found in other Polynesian languages, including Māori (*Hawaiki*), Rarotongan (*ʻAvaiki*) and Samoan (*Savaiʻi*).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] According to linguists Pukui and Elbert, "elsewhere in Polynesia, *Hawaiʻi* or a cognate is the name of the underworld or of the ancestral home, but in Hawaii, the name has no meaning".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1978, Hawaiian was added to the Constitution of the State of Hawaii as an official state language alongside English.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The title of the state constitution is *The Constitution of the State of Hawaii*.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Article XV, Section 1 of the Constitution uses *The State of Hawaii*.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Diacritics were not used because the document, drafted in 1949, predates the use of the *ʻokina* ⟨ʻ⟩ and the *kahakō* in modern Hawaiian orthography.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The exact spelling of the state's name in the Hawaiian language is *Hawaiʻi*.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Seven are inhabited, but only six are open to tourists and locals.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Niʻihau is privately managed by brothers Bruce and Keith Robinson; access is restricted to those who have their permission.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] This island is also home to native Hawaiians.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Access to uninhabited Kahoʻolawe island is also restricted and anyone who enters without permission is subject to arrest.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Kahoʻolawe may also be dangerous since it was a military base during the world wars and could still have unexploded ordnance.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Hawaiian archipelago is 2,000 mi (3,200 km) southwest of the contiguous United States.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii is the southernmost U.S. state and the second farthest west, after Alaska.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Like Alaska, Hawaii borders no other U.S. state.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] It is the only U.S. state not in North America, as it is in Oceania, and the only one completely surrounded by water and entirely an archipelago.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In addition to the eight main islands, the state has many smaller islands and islets.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Northwestern Hawaiian Islands is a group of nine small, older islands northwest of Kauaʻi that extends from Nīhoa to Kure Atoll; they are remnants of much larger volcanic mountains.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Across the archipelago are around 130 small rocks and islets, such as Molokini, which are made up of either volcanic or marine sedimentary rock.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaiʻi's tallest mountain, Mauna Kea, is 13,796 ft (4,205 m) above mean sea level; but it is taller than Mount Everest when measured from the base of the mountain, which is on the floor of the Pacific Ocean, rising about 33,500 feet (10,200 m).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Hawaiian islands were formed by volcanic activity initiated at an undersea magma source called the Hawaiʻi hotspot.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The process continues to build islands; the tectonic plate beneath much of the Pacific Ocean continually moves northwest and the hotspot remains stationary, slowly creating new volcanoes.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Because of the hotspot's location, all active land volcanoes are on the southern half of Hawaiʻi Island.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The newest volcano, Kamaʻehuakanaloa (formerly Lōʻihi), is south of the coast of Hawaiʻi Island.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The last volcanic eruption outside Hawaiʻi Island occurred at Haleakalā on Maui before the late 18th century, possibly hundreds of years earlier.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1790, Kīlauea exploded; it is the deadliest eruption known to have occurred in the modern era in what is now the United States.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Up to 5,405 warriors and their families marching on Kīlauea were killed by the eruption.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Volcanic activity and subsequent erosion have created impressive geological features.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii Island has the second-highest point among the world's islands.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] On the volcanoes' flanks, slope instability has generated damaging earthquakes and related tsunamis, particularly in 1868 and 1975.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Catastrophic debris avalanches on the ocean island volcanoes' submerged flanks have created steep cliffs.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Kīlauea erupted in May 2018, opening 22 fissure vents on its eastern rift zone.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Leilani Estates and Lanipuna Gardens are within this territory.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The eruption destroyed at least 36 buildings and this, coupled with the lava flows and the sulfur dioxide fumes, necessitated the evacuation of more than 2,000 inhabitants from their neighborhoods.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The islands of Hawaiʻi are distant from other land habitats, and life is thought to have arrived there by wind, waves (i.e., ocean currents), and wings (i.e., birds, insects, and seeds they may have carried on their feathers).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaiʻi has more endangered species and has lost a higher percentage of its endemic species than any other U.S. state.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The endemic plant *Brighamia* now requires hand pollination because its natural pollinator is presumed to be extinct.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The two species of *Brighamia*—*B. rockii* and *B. insignis*—are represented in the wild by around 120 individual plants.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] To ensure that these plants set seed, biologists rappel down 3,000-foot (910 m) cliffs to brush pollen onto their stigmas.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The archipelago's extant main islands have been above the ocean's surface for less than 10 million years, a fraction of the time biological colonization and evolution have occurred there.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The islands are known for the environmental diversity that occurs on high mountains within a trade winds field.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Native Hawaiians developed complex horticultural practices to utilize the surrounding ecosystem for agriculture.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Cultural practices developed to enshrine values of environmental stewardship and reciprocity with the natural world, resulting in widespread biodiversity and intricate social and environmental relationships that still persist.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The rainy climate affects soil development, which largely determines ground permeability and the distribution of streams and wetlands.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Several areas in Hawaii are under the National Park Service's protection.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii has two national parks: Haleakalā National Park, near Kula on Maui, which features the dormant volcano Haleakalā that formed east Maui; and Hawaii Volcanoes National Park, in the southeast region of Hawaiʻi Island, which includes the active volcano Kīlauea and its rift zones.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Other areas under the National Park Service's control include Ala Kahakai National Historic Trail on Hawaiʻi Island and the USS *Arizona* Memorial at Pearl Harbor on Oʻahu.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Bush proclaimed the Papahānaumokuākea Marine National Monument on June 15, 2006.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The monument covers roughly 140,000 square miles (360,000 km2) of reefs, atolls, and shallow and deep sea out to 50 miles (80 km) offshore in the Pacific Ocean—an area larger than all the national parks in the U.S. combined.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Temperatures and humidity tend to be less extreme because of near-constant trade winds from the east.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Summer highs reach around 88 °F (31 °C) during the day, with lows of 75 °F (24 °C) at night.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Winter day temperatures are usually around 83 °F (28 °C); at low elevation they seldom dip below 65 °F (18 °C) at night.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Snow, not usually associated with the tropics, falls at 13,800 feet (4,200 m) on Mauna Kea and Mauna Loa on Hawaii Island in the winter.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Mount Waiʻaleʻale on Kauaʻi has the second-highest average annual rainfall on Earth, about 460 inches (12,000 mm) per year.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Most of Hawaii experiences only two seasons; the dry season runs from May to October and the wet season is from October to April.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] With climate change, Hawaiʻi is getting drier and hotter.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The highest temperature recorded in the state, in Pahala on April 27, 1931, is 100 °F (38 °C), tied with Alaska as the lowest record high temperature observed in a U.S. state.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaiʻi's record low temperature is 12 °F (−11 °C), observed in May 1979 on the summit of Mauna Kea.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaiʻi is the only state to have never recorded subzero Fahrenheit temperatures.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Climates vary considerably on each island; they can be divided into windward and leeward (*koʻolau* and *kona*, respectively) areas based upon location relative to the higher mountains.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii has a decades-long history of hosting more military space for the United States than any other territory or state.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] This military activity has taken a sharp toll on the environmental health of the Hawaiian archipelago, degrading its beaches and soil and making some places entirely unsafe due to unexploded ordnance.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] According to scholar Winona LaDuke: "The vast militarization of Hawaii has profoundly damaged the land.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] According to the Environmental Protection Agency, there are more federal hazardous waste sites in Hawaii—31—than in any other U.S. state." Hawaii State Representative Roy Takumi writes in "Challenging U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] After the rise of sugarcane plantations in the mid-19th century, island ecology changed dramatically.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Plantations require massive quantities of water, and European and American plantation owners transformed the land in order to access it, primarily by building tunnels to divert water from the mountains to the plantations, constructing reservoirs, and digging wells.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] These changes have made lasting impacts on the land and continue to contribute to resource scarcity for Native Hawaiians.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] According to Stanford scientist and scholar Sibyl Diver, Indigenous Hawaiians engage in a reciprocal relationship with the land, "based on principles of mutual caretaking, reciprocity and sharing".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] This relationship ensures the longevity, sustainability, and natural cycles of growth and decay, as well as cultivating a sense of respect for the land and humility towards one's place in an ecosystem.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The tourism industry's ongoing expansion and its pressure on local systems of ecology, cultural tradition and infrastructure creates a conflict between economic and environmental health.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 2020, the Center for Biological Diversity reported on the plastic pollution of Hawaii's Kamilo beach, citing "massive piles of plastic waste".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Invasive species are spreading, and chemical and pathogenic runoff is contaminating groundwater and coastal waters.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In June 2022, a lawsuit was filed against the Hawaii Department of Transportation claiming that the state's pro-fossil fuel transportation policies violated their state constitutional rights and created "untenable levels of greenhouse gas emissions." The lawsuit, *Navahine F v.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaii Department of Transportation*, was filed by 13 young people in the state, most of whom are Indigenous.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The resulting legal settlement will force the state to move more aggressively towards a zero-emission transportation system by 2045.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaiʻi is one of two U.S. states, along with Texas, that were internationally recognized sovereign nations before becoming U.S. states.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Kingdom of Hawaiʻi was sovereign from 1810 until 1893, when resident American and European capitalists and landholders overthrew the monarchy.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaiʻi was an independent republic from 1894 until August 12, 1898, when it officially became a U.S. territory.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaiʻi was admitted as a U.S. state on August 21, 1959.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The date of human arrival and habitation of the Hawaiian Islands is the subject of academic debate.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Early archaeological studies suggested that Polynesians from the Marquesas Islands or Society Islands may have arrived as early as the 3rd century CE.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Some archaeologists and historians think it was a later wave of immigrants from Tahiti around 1100 CE who introduced a new line of high chiefs, the kapu system, the practice of human sacrifice, and the building of *heiau*.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] This later immigration is detailed in Hawaiian mythology (*moʻolelo*) about Paʻao.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Other authors say there is no archaeological or linguistic evidence of a later influx of Tahitian settlers and that Paʻao must be regarded as a myth.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] More recent archaeological studies further suggest that the first settlement of Hawaii was not until around 900–1200 CE.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The islands' history is marked by a slow, steady growth in population and the size of the chiefdoms, which grew to encompass whole islands.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Local chiefs, called aliʻi, ruled their settlements, and launched wars to extend their influence and defend their communities from predatory rivals.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Ancient Hawaiʻi was a caste-based society, much like that of Hindus in India.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Population growth was facilitated by ecological and agricultural practices that combined upland agriculture (*manuka*), ocean fishing (*makai*), fishponds and gardening systems.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] These systems were upheld by spiritual and religious beliefs, like the *lokahi*, that linked cultural continuity with the health of the natural world.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] According to Hawaiian scholar Mililani Trask, the *lokahi* symbolizes the "greatest of the traditions, values, and practices of our people ...
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] There are three points in the triangle—the Creator, *Akua*; the peoples of the earth, *Kanaka Maoli*; and the land, the *ʻaina*.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In January 1778, British Captain James Cook encountered the Hawaiian Islands serendipitously while crossing the Pacific during his third voyage of exploration.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] This marked the first documented contact by a European explorer with Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Cook named the archipelago "the Sandwich Islands" in honor of his sponsor, John Montagu, 4th Earl of Sandwich.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Cook returned to the Hawaiian Islands in 1779 to resupply and overwinter, anchoring in Kealakakua off Hawaii Island for one month.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Relations with the local people were peaceful at first, then deteriorated, and Cook was among those killed when violence broke out between the British and local Hawaiians.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] After Cook, Hawaii was not visited by any foreign ships for seven years but after 1786 visits became increasingly frequent.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] At the end of the 18th century, the maritime fur trade developed between the northwest coast of North America and Asia, bringing ships of many nations to the North Pacific Ocean.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Hawaiian islands became established as a convenient source of supplies and destination for overwintering not only for fur traders but also ships engaged in general cross-Pacific commerce.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Historian Ralph Kuykendall has called the impact of these foreign visitors on the hitherto isolated Hawaiian Islands an "invasion" that "little by little overwhelmed the old culture of the islands".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Native Hawaiians were vulnerable to Eurasian diseases to which they had less resistance.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] It is estimated that the native population had declined by half 40 years after Cook's arrival and continued to decline throughout the 19th century.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] During the 1850s, measles killed a fifth of Hawaiʻi's people.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] During the 1780s and early 1790s, the Hawaiian Islands were divided among several warring chiefdoms.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1795, the fighting ended when Kamehameha, then a chief (*aliʻi*) of Hawaii Island, conquered most of the main islands in the archipelago (including Maui and Oʻahu), then founded the Hawaiian Kingdom and the House of Kamehameha dynasty.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Kauaʻi (with nearby Niʻihau) remained independent until 1810, when it joined the Hawaiian Kingdom peacefully.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] After Kamehameha II inherited the throne in 1819, American Protestant missionaries to Hawaiʻi converted many Hawaiians to Christianity.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Missionaries have argued that one function of missionary work was to "civilize" and "purify" perceived heathenism in the New World.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] According to historical archaeologist James L.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Flexner, "missionaries provided the moral means to rationalize conquest and wholesale conversion to Christianity".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] But rather than abandon traditional beliefs entirely, most native Hawaiians merged their Indigenous religion with Christianity.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Missionaries used their influence to end many traditional practices, including the *kapu* system, the prevailing legal system before European contact, and *heiau*, or "temples" to religious figures.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] *Kapu*, which typically translates to "the sacred", refers to social regulations (like gender and class restrictions) based on spiritual beliefs.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Under the missionaries' guidance, laws against gambling, consuming alcohol, dancing the *hula*, breaking the Sabbath, and polygamy were enacted.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Without the *kapu* system, many temples and priestly statuses were jeopardized, idols were burned, and participation in Christianity increased.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] When Kamehameha III inherited the throne at age 12, his advisors pressured him to merge Christianity with traditional Hawaiian ways.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Under the guidance of his *kuhina nui* (his mother and coregent Elizabeth Kaʻahumanu) and British allies, Hawaiʻi turned into a Christian monarchy with the signing of the 1840 Constitution.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hiram Bingham I, a prominent Protestant missionary, was a trusted adviser to the monarchy during this period.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Other missionaries and their descendants became active in commercial and political affairs, leading to conflicts between the monarchy and its restive American subjects.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Missionaries from each major group administered to the leper colony at Kalaupapa on Molokaʻi, which was established in 1866 and operated well into the 20th century.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The best known were Father Damien and Mother Marianne Cope, both of whom were canonized in the early 21st century as Roman Catholic saints.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The death of the bachelor King Kamehameha V—who did not name an heir—resulted in the popular election of Lunalilo over Kalākaua.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Lunalilo died the next year, also without naming an heir.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1874, the election was contested within the legislature between Kalākaua and Emma, Queen Consort of Kamehameha IV.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] After riots broke out, the U.S. and Britain landed troops on the islands to restore order.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Legislative Assembly chose King Kalākaua as monarch by a vote of 39 to 6 on February 12, 1874.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1887, Kalākaua was forced to sign the 1887 Constitution of the Kingdom of Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Drafted by white businessmen and lawyers, the document stripped the king of much of his authority.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] It established a property qualification for voting that effectively disenfranchised most Hawaiians and immigrant laborers and favored the wealthier, white elite.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Resident whites were allowed to vote but resident Asians were not.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] As the 1887 Constitution was signed under threat of violence, it is known as the Bayonet Constitution.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] King Kalākaua, reduced to a figurehead, reigned until his death in 1891.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] His sister, Queen Liliʻuokalani, succeeded him; she was the last monarch of Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1893, Liliʻuokalani announced plans for a new constitution to proclaim herself an absolute monarch.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] On January 14, 1893, a group of mostly Euro-American business leaders and residents formed the Committee of Safety to stage a coup d'état against the kingdom and seek annexation by the United States.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Stevens, responding to a request from the Committee of Safety, summoned a company of U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] According to historian William Russ, the monarchy was unable to protect itself.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The treason trials of 1892 brought together the main players in the 1893 overthrow.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Stevens voiced support for Native Hawaiian revolutionaries; William R.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Castle, a Committee of Safety member, served as a defense counsel in the treason trials; Alfred Stedman Hartwell, the 1893 annexation commissioner, led the defense effort; and Sanford B.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Dole ruled as a supreme court justice against acts of conspiracy and treason.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] On January 17, 1893, a small group of sugar and pineapple-growing businessmen, aided by the U.S. minister to Hawaii and backed by heavily armed U.S. soldiers and marines, deposed Queen Liliʻuokalani and installed a provisional government composed of members of the Committee of Safety.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] According to scholar Lydia Kualapai and Hawaii State Representative Roy Takumi, this committee was formed against the will of Indigenous Hawaiian voters, who constituted the majority of voters at the time.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] According to scholar J Kehaulani Kauanui, it consisted of "thirteen white men".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Stevens conspired with U.S. citizens to overthrow the monarchy.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] After the overthrow, Dole, a citizen of Hawaii and cousin to James Dole, owner of Hawaiian Fruit Company, a company that benefited from the annexation of Hawaii, became president of the republic when the Provisional Government of Hawaiʻi ended on July 4, 1894.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Controversy ensued in the following years as the queen tried to regain her throne.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Following the January 1893 coup that deposed Liliʻuokalani, many royalists were preparing to overthrow the white-led Republic of Hawaiʻi oligarchy.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hundreds of rifles were covertly shipped to Hawaii and hidden in caves nearby.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] As armed troops came and went, a Republic of Hawaiʻi patrol discovered the rebel group.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] On January 6, 1895, gunfire began on both sides and later the rebels were surrounded and captured.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Over the next 10 days several skirmishes occurred, until the last armed opposition surrendered or were captured.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Republic of Hawaiʻi took 123 troops into custody as prisoners of war.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The mass arrest of nearly 300 more men and women, including Queen Liliʻuokalani, as political prisoners was intended to incapacitate the political resistance against the ruling oligarchy.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In March 1895, a military tribunal convicted 170 prisoners of treason and sentenced six troops to be "hung by the neck" until dead, according to historian Ronald Williams Jr.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The other prisoners were variously sentenced to from five to thirty-five years' imprisonment at hard labor, while those convicted of lesser charges received sentences from six months' to six years' imprisonment at hard labor.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The queen was sentenced to five years in prison, but spent eight months under house arrest until she was released on parole.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The total number of arrests related to the 1895 Kaua Kūloko was 406 people on a summary list of statistics, published by the government of the Republic of Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The administration of President Grover Cleveland commissioned the Blount Report, which concluded that the removal of Liliʻuokalani had been illegal.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Commissioner Blount found the U.S. and its minister guilty on all counts including the overthrow, the landing of the marines, and the recognition of the provisional government.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The U.S. government first demanded that Queen Liliʻuokalani be reinstated, but the Provisional Government refused.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] On December 23, 1893, the response from the Provisional Government of Hawaii, authored by President Sanford B.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Dole, was received by Cleveland's representative Minister Albert S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Willis and emphasized that the Provisional Government of Hawaii "unhesitatingly" rejected the demand from the Cleveland Administration.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Congress conducted an independent investigation, and on February 26, 1894, submitted the Morgan Report, which found all parties, including Stevens—with the exception of the queen—"not guilty" and not responsible for the coup.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Partisans on both sides of the debate questioned the accuracy and impartiality of both the Blount and Morgan reports over the events of 1893.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1993, Congress passed a joint Apology Resolution regarding the overthrow; it was signed by President Bill Clinton.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] After William McKinley won the 1896 U.S. presidential election, advocates pressed to annex the Republic of Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The previous president, Grover Cleveland, was a friend of Queen Liliʻuokalani.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] McKinley was open to persuasion by U.S. expansionists and by annexationists from Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] He met with three non-native annexationists: Lorrin A.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Thurston, Francis March Hatch and William Ansel Kinney.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] After negotiations in June 1897, Secretary of State John Sherman agreed to a treaty of annexation with these representatives of the Republic of Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The majority of Native Hawaiians vociferously opposed annexation and found a spokesperson in former queen Liliʻuokalani.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Opposition crystallized around the Kūʻē Petition drive of 1897, in which 21,269 signatures opposing annexation were procured by members of Hui Aloha ʻĀina (Hawaiian Patriotic League).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] These petitions were hand-carried to Washington and delivered to the United States Senate by a commission of Native Hawaiian delegates.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The petition swayed several key votes and contributed to the Senate's ultimately voting against ratification of the treaty.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] However, in 1898, the Newlands Resolution was introduced in the US House of Representatives.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The resolution would legalize the annexation of the Republic of Hawaii to the United States, becoming the Territory of Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Newlands Resolution was passed by the House on June 15, 1898, by a vote of 209 to 91 and by the Senate on July 6, 1898, by a vote of 42 to 21.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] It was then signed into law by president McKinley.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In 1900, Hawaiʻi was granted self-governance and retained ʻIolani Palace as the territorial capitol building.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Despite several attempts to become a state, Hawaii remained a territory for 60 years.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Plantation owners and capitalists, who maintained control through financial institutions such as the Big Five, found territorial status convenient because they remained able to import cheap, foreign labor.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Such immigration and labor practices were prohibited in many states.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Puerto Rican immigration to Hawaiʻi began in 1899, when Puerto Rico's sugar industry was devastated by a hurricane, causing a worldwide shortage of sugar and a huge demand for sugar from Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Hawaiian sugarcane plantation owners began to recruit experienced, unemployed laborers in Puerto Rico.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Two waves of Korean immigration to Hawaiʻi occurred in the 20th century.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The first wave arrived between 1903 and 1924; the second wave began in 1965 after President Lyndon B.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Johnson signed the Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965, which removed racial and national barriers and resulted in significantly altering the demographic mix in the U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Oʻahu was the target of a surprise attack on Pearl Harbor by the Empire of Japan on December 7, 1941.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The attack on Pearl Harbor and other military and naval installations, carried out by aircraft and by midget submarines, brought the United States into World War II.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In the 1950s, the plantation owners' power was broken by the descendants of immigrant laborers, who were born in Hawaiʻi and were U.S. citizens.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] They voted against the Hawaiʻi Republican Party, strongly supported by plantation owners.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The new majority voted for the Democratic Party of Hawaiʻi, which dominated territorial and state politics for more than 40 years.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Eager to gain full representation in Congress and the Electoral College, residents actively campaigned for statehood.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In Washington, there was talk that Hawaiʻi would be a Republican Party stronghold.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] As a result, the admission of Hawaii was matched with the admission of Alaska, which was seen as a Democratic Party stronghold.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] These predictions proved inaccurate; as of 2017, Hawaiʻi almost always votes Democratic, while Alaska typically votes Republican.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] During the Cold War, Hawaiʻi became an important site for U.S. cultural diplomacy, military training, research, and as a staging ground for the U.S. war in Vietnam.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] In March 1959, Congress passed the Hawaiʻi Admissions Act, which U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The act excluded Palmyra Atoll from statehood; it had been part of the Kingdom and Territory of Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] On June 27, 1959, a referendum asked residents of Hawaiʻi to vote on the statehood bill; 94.3% voted in favor of statehood and 5.7% opposed it.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The referendum asked voters to choose between accepting the Act and remaining a U.S. territory.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The United Nations' Special Committee on Decolonization later removed Hawaiʻi from its list of non-self-governing territories.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] After attaining statehood, Hawaiʻi quickly modernized through construction and a rapidly growing tourism economy.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] Later, state programs promoted Hawaiian culture.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p01] The Hawaiʻi State Constitutional Convention of 1978 created institutions such as the Office of Hawaiian Affairs to promote indigenous language and culture.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] After Europeans and mainland Americans first arrived during the Kingdom of Hawaii period, the overall population of Hawaii—which until that time composed solely of Indigenous Hawaiians—fell dramatically.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Many people of the Indigenous Hawaiian population died to foreign diseases, declining from an estimated 300,000 in the 1770s, to 60,000 in the 1850s, to 24,000 in 1920.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Other estimates for the pre-contact population range from 150,000 to 1.5 million.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The population of Hawaii began to finally increase after an influx of primarily Asian settlers that arrived as migrant laborers at the end of the 19th century.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 1923, 42% of the population was of Japanese descent, 9% of Chinese descent, and 16% Native Hawaiian descent.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii's population has been declining steadily since 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The increasing cost of living and needing to import supplies is cited as the top reason for relocating to the U.S. mainland, followed by climate change, including more drought, wildfires, as well as rising seas.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 2010, 156,000 residents declared themselves to be solely of Native Hawaiian ancestry, just over half the estimated pre-contact population.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] An additional 371,000 declared themselves to possess Native Hawaiian ancestry in combination with one or more other races (including other Polynesian groups, but mostly Asian or White).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 2018, the United States Census Bureau estimated the population of Hawaii to be 1,420,491, a decrease of 7,047 from the previous year but an increase of 60,190 (4.42%) since 2010.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] This includes a natural increase of 48,111 (96,028 births minus 47,917 deaths) and an increase due to net migration of 16,956 people into the state.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Immigration from outside the United States resulted in a net increase of 30,068; migration within the country produced a net loss of 13,112 people.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The center of population of Hawaii is located on the island of Oʻahu.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Large numbers of Native Hawaiians have moved to Las Vegas, which has been called the "ninth island" of Hawaii.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii has a *de facto* population of over 1.4 million, due in part to a large number of military personnel and tourist residents.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Oʻahu is the most populous island, and has the highest population density with a resident population of just under one million in 597 square miles (1,546 km2), approximately 1,650 people per square mile.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii's 1.4 million residents, spread across 6,000 square miles (15,500 km2) of land, result in an average population density of 188.6 persons per square mile.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The state has a lower population density than Ohio and Illinois.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The average projected lifespan of people born in Hawaii in 2000 is 79.8 years; 77.1 years if male, 82.5 if female—longer than the average lifespan of any other U.S. state.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] As of 2011 the U.S. military reported it had 42,371 personnel on the islands.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 5,967 homeless people in Hawaii.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 2018, the top countries of origin for immigrants in Hawaii were the Philippines, China, Japan, Korea, and the Marshall Islands.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to the 2020 United States Census, Hawaii had a population of 1,455,271.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The state's population identified as 37.2% Asian; 25.3% Multiracial; 22.9% White; 10.8% Native Hawaiians and other Pacific Islanders; 9.5% Hispanic and Latinos of any race; 1.6% Black or African American; 1.8% from some other race; and 0.3% Native American and Alaskan Native.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii has the highest percentage of Asian Americans and multiracial Americans and the lowest percentage of White Americans of any state.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It is the only state where people who identify as Asian Americans are the largest ethnic group.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 2012, 14.5% of the resident population under age 1 was non-Hispanic white.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Over 120,000 (8.8%) Hispanic and Latino Americans live in Hawaii.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Multiracial Americans constitute almost 25% of Hawaii's population, exceeding 320,000 people.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii is the only state to have a tri-racial group as its largest multiracial group, one that includes white, Asian and Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander (22% of all multiracial population).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The non-Hispanic White population numbers around 310,000—just over 20% of the population.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The multi-racial population outnumbers the non-Hispanic white population by about 10,000 people.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 1970, the Census Bureau reported Hawaii's population was 38.8% white and 57.7% Asian and Pacific Islander.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] There are more than 80,000 Indigenous Hawaiians—5.9% of the population.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Including those with partial ancestry, Samoan Americans constitute 2.8% of Hawaii's population, and Tongan Americans constitute 0.6%.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The five largest European ancestries in Hawaii are German (7.4%), Irish (5.2%), English (4.6%), Portuguese (4.3%) and Italian (2.7%).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] About 82.2% of the state's residents were born in the United States.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Roughly 75% of foreign-born residents originate from Asia.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It was expected to be one of three states that would not have a non-Hispanic white plurality in 2014; the other two are California and New Mexico.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The third group of foreigners to arrive in Hawaii were from China.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Chinese workers on Western trading ships settled in Hawaii starting in 1789.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 1820, the first American missionaries arrived to preach Christianity and teach the Hawaiians Western ways.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] As of 2015, a large proportion of Hawaii's population have Asian ancestry—especially Filipino, Japanese and Chinese.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Many are descendants of immigrants brought to work on the sugarcane plantations in the mid-to-late 19th century.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The first 153 Japanese immigrants arrived in Hawaii on June 19, 1868.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] They were not approved by the then-current Japanese government because the contract was between a broker and the Tokugawa shogunate—by then replaced by the Meiji Restoration.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The first Japanese current-government-approved immigrants arrived on February 9, 1885, after Kalākaua's petition to Emperor Meiji when Kalākaua visited Japan in 1881.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Almost 13,000 Portuguese migrants had arrived by 1899; they also worked on the sugarcane plantations.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] By 1901, more than 5,000 Puerto Ricans were living in Hawaii.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] English and Hawaiian are listed as Hawaii's official languages in the state's 1978 constitution, in Article XV, Section 4.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] However, the use of Hawaiian is limited because the constitution specifies that "Hawaiian shall be required for public acts and transactions only as provided by law".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiʻi Creole English, locally referred to as "Pidgin", is the native language of many native residents and is a second language for many others.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The 2000 Census found that 73.4% of Hawaii residents age 5 and older exclusively spoke English at home.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to the 2008 American Community Survey, 74.6% of Hawaii's residents older than 5 spoke only English at home.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In their homes, 21.0% of state residents speak an additional Asian language, 2.6% speak Spanish, 1.6% speak other Indo-European languages and 0.2% speak another language.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] After English, other languages popularly spoken in the state are Tagalog, Ilocano, and Japanese.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] 5.4% of residents speak Tagalog, which includes non-native speakers of Filipino, a Tagalog-based national and co-official language of the Philippines; 5.0% speak Japanese and 4.0% speak Ilocano; 1.2% speak Chinese, 1.7% speak Hawaiian; 1.7% speak Spanish; 1.6% speak Korean; and 1.0% speak Samoan.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Hawaiian language has about 2,000 native speakers, about 0.15% of the total population.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to the United States Census, there were more than 24,000 total speakers of the language in Hawaii in 2006–2008.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiian is a Polynesian member of the Austronesian language family.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It is closely related to other Polynesian languages, such as Marquesan, Tahitian, Māori, Rapa Nui (the language of Easter Island), and less closely to Samoan and Tongan.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to Schütz, the Marquesans colonized the archipelago in roughly 300 CE and were later followed by waves of seafarers from the Society Islands, Samoa and Tonga.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] These Polynesians remained in the islands; they eventually became the Hawaiian people and their languages evolved into the Hawaiian language.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Kimura and Wilson say: "[l]inguists agree that Hawaiian is closely related to Eastern Polynesian, with a particularly strong link in the Southern Marquesas, and a secondary link in Tahiti, which may be explained by voyaging between the Hawaiian and Society Islands".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Before the arrival of Captain James Cook, the Hawaiian language had no written form.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] That form was developed mainly by American Protestant missionaries between 1820 and 1826 who assigned to the Hawaiian phonemes letters from the Latin alphabet.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Interest in Hawaiian increased significantly in the late 20th century.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] With the help of the Office of Hawaiian Affairs, specially designated immersion schools in which all subjects would be taught in Hawaiian were established.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The University of Hawaiʻi developed a Hawaiian-language graduate studies program.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Municipal codes were altered to favor Hawaiian place and street names for new civic developments.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiian distinguishes between long and short vowel sounds.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In modern practice, vowel length is indicated with a macron (*kahakō*).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiian-language newspapers (*nūpepa*) published from 1834 to 1948 and traditional native speakers of Hawaiian generally omit the marks in their own writing.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The ʻokina and kahakō are intended to capture the proper pronunciation of Hawaiian words.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Hawaiian language uses the glottal stop (*ʻOkina*) as a consonant.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It is written as a symbol similar to the apostrophe or left-hanging (opening) single quotation mark.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The keyboard layout used for Hawaiian is QWERTY.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The development of Hawaiian Pidgin began with Pidgin Hawaiian, an earlier pidgin that formed in the 1790s during initial contact between Native Hawaiians and foreigners.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] As plantation laborers from various countries arrived, a new pidgin based on English evolved to facilitate communication among workers and supervisors.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] By the early 20th century, children of these plantation workers began acquiring **Hawaiian Pidgin** as their first language, leading to its creolization.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] This transition marked the emergence of HCE as a fully developed creole language.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] HCE incorporates Hawaiian words, especially in place names and terms for local flora and fauna.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] For instance, the Hawaiian term for tuna, "ahi," is commonly used in HCE.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Additionally, certain English words have adapted meanings; "aunty" and "uncle" are used to address any respected elder, regardless of familial relation.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Some expressions from HCE have permeated other communities, particularly through surfing culture.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Terms like "brah" (brother) and "da kine" (a versatile placeholder term) have gained recognition beyond Hawaiʻi.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Census Bureau recognized Hawaiian Pidgin as an official language in Hawaiʻi, reflecting its widespread use among residents.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Despite this recognition, debates continue about its role in education and its impact on learning Standard English.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiʻi Sign Language, a sign language for the Deaf based on the Hawaiian language, has been in use in the islands since the early 1800s.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It is dwindling in numbers due to American Sign Language supplanting HSL through schooling and various other domains.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii is among the most religiously diverse states in the U.S., with one in ten residents practicing a non-Christian faith.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Roughly one-quarter to half the population identify as unaffiliated and nonreligious, making Hawaii one of the most secular states as well.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Christianity remains the majority religion, represented mainly by various Protestant groups and Catholicism.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The second-largest religion is Buddhism, which comprises a larger proportion of the population than in any other state; it is concentrated in the Japanese community.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Native Hawaiians continue to engage in traditional religious and spiritual practices today, often adhering to Christian and traditional beliefs at the same time.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Cathedral Basilica of Our Lady of Peace and the Co-Cathedral of Saint Theresa of the Child Jesus serve as seats of the Diocese of Honolulu.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Eastern Orthodox community is centered around the Saints Constantine and Helen Greek Orthodox Cathedral of the Pacific.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Nondenominational churches collectively have 128 congregations and 32,000 members.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] 1) Until 2016, data for births of Asian origin, included also births of the Pacific Islander group.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] group; persons of Hispanic origin may be of any race.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The percentage surviving, is the percent of the population that would survive to certain age, if their life conditions in a given year, were extrapolated to their whole life.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii has had a long history of LGBTQIA+ identities.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] *Māhū* ("in the middle") were a precolonial third gender with traditional spiritual and social roles, widely respected as healers.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Homosexual relationships known as *aikāne* were widespread and normal in ancient Hawaiian society.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Among men, *aikāne* relationships often began as teens and continued throughout their adult lives, even if they also maintained heterosexual partners.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] While *aikāne* usually refers to male homosexuality, some stories also refer to women, implying that women may have been involved in *aikāne* relationships as well.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Journals written by Captain Cook's crew record that many *aliʻi* (hereditary nobles) also engaged in *aikāne* relationships, and Kamehameha the Great, the founder and first ruler of the Kingdom of Hawaii, was also known to participate.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Cook's second lieutenant and co-astronomer James King observed that "all the chiefs had them", and recounts that Cook was actually asked by one chief to leave King behind, considering the role a great honor.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiian scholar Lilikalā Kameʻeleihiwa notes that *aikāne* served a practical purpose of building mutual trust and cohesion; "If you didn't sleep with a man, how could you trust him when you went into battle?
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] As Western colonial influences intensified in the late 19th and early 20th century, the word *aikāne* was expurgated of its original sexual meaning, and in print simply meant "friend".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Nonetheless, in Hawaiian language publications its metaphorical meaning can still mean either "friend" or "lover" without stigmatization.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] A 2012 Gallup poll found that Hawaii had the largest proportion of LGBTQIA+ adults in the U.S., at 5.1%, an estimated 53,966 individuals.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The number of same-sex couple households in 2010 was 3,239, representing a 35.5% increase from a decade earlier.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 2013, Hawaii became the fifteenth U.S. state to legalize same-sex marriage; this reportedly boosted tourism by $217 million.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The history of Hawaii's economy can be traced through a succession of dominant industries: sandalwood, whaling, sugarcane, pineapple, the military, tourism and education.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] By the 1840s, sugar plantations had gained a strong foothold in the Hawaiian economy, due to a high demand of sugar in the United States and rapid transport via steamships.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Sugarcane plantations were tightly controlled by American missionary families and businessmen known as "the Big Five", who monopolized control of the sugar industry's profits.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] By the time Hawaiian annexation was being considered in 1898, sugarcane producers turned to cultivating tropical fruits like pineapple, which became the principal export for Hawaii's plantation economy.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Since statehood in 1959, tourism has been the largest industry, contributing 24.3% of the gross state product (GSP) in 1997, despite efforts to diversify.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 2025, Hawaii's gross state product was $124.6 billion and the per capita personal income for Hawaii residents was $76,592.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiian exports include food and clothing.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] These industries play a small role in the Hawaiian economy, due to the shipping distance to viable markets, such as the West Coast of the United States.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The state's food exports include coffee, macadamia nuts, pineapple, livestock, sugarcane, and honey.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] By weight, honey bees may be the state's most valuable export.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to the Hawaii Agricultural Statistics Service, in 2002 agricultural sales were US$370.9 million from diversified agriculture, US$100.6 million from pineapple, and US$64.3 million from sugarcane.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii's relatively consistent climate has attracted the seed industry, which is able to test three generations of crops per year on the islands, compared with one or two on the mainland.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Seeds yielded US$264 million in 2012, supporting 1,400 workers.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] As of August 2025, the state's unemployment rate was 2.7%.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The historically lowest unemployment rate of 2.0% was recorded in December 2017, and its highest, 22.0%, in April 2020.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 2025, 99.3% of Hawaii's businesses were small businesses, employing 49.6% of the state's workforce.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 2009, the United States military spent US$12.2 billion in Hawaii, accounting for 18% of spending in the state for that year.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] 75,000 United States Department of Defense personnel live in Hawaii.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to a 2013 study by Phoenix Marketing International, Hawaii at that time had the fourth-largest number of millionaires per capita in the United States, with a ratio of 7.2%.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Tax is collected by the Hawaii Department of Taxation.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Most government revenue comes from personal income taxes and a general excise tax (GET) levied primarily on businesses; there is no statewide tax on sales, personal property, or stock transfers, while the effective property tax rate is among the lowest in the country.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The high rate of tourism means that millions of visitors generate public revenue through GET and the hotel room tax.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] However, Hawaii residents generally pay among the most state taxes per person in the U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Tax Foundation of Hawaii considers the state's tax burden too high, claiming that it contributes to higher prices and the perception of an unfriendly business climate.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The nonprofit Tax Foundation ranks Hawaii third in income tax burden and second in its overall tax burden, though notes that a significant portion of taxes are borne by tourists.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Former State Senator Sam Slom attributed Hawaii's comparatively high tax rate to the fact that the state government is responsible for education, health care, and social services that are usually handled at a county or municipal level in most other states.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The cost of living in Hawaii, specifically Honolulu, is high compared to that of most major U.S. cities, although it is 6.7% lower than in New York City and 3.6% lower than in San Francisco.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] These numbers may not take into account some costs, such as increased travel costs for flights, additional shipping fees, and the loss of promotional participation opportunities for customers outside the contiguous U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] While some online stores offer free shipping on orders to Hawaii, many merchants exclude Hawaii, Alaska, Puerto Rico and certain other U.S. territories.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiian Electric Industries, a privately owned company, provides 95% of the state's population with electricity, mostly from fossil-fuel power stations.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Average electricity prices in October 2014 (36.41 cents per kilowatt-hour) were nearly three times the national average (12.58 cents per kilowatt-hour) and 80% higher than the second-highest state, Connecticut.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The median home value in Hawaii in the 2000 U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Census was US$272,700, while the national median home value was US$119,600.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii home values were the highest of all states, including California with a median home value of US$211,500.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Research from the National Association of Realtors places the 2010 median sale price of a single family home in Honolulu, Hawaii, at US$607,600 and the U.S. median sales price at US$173,200.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The sale price of single family homes in Hawaii was the highest of any U.S. city in 2010, just above that of the Silicon Valley area of California (US$602,000).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii's very high cost of living is the result of several interwoven factors of the global economy in addition to domestic U.S. government trade policy.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Like other regions with desirable weather year-round, such as California, Arizona and Florida, Hawaii's residents can be considered to be subject to a "sunshine tax".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] This situation is further exacerbated by the natural factors of geography and world distribution that lead to higher prices for goods due to increased shipping costs, a problem which many island states and territories suffer from as well.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The higher costs to ship goods across an ocean may be further increased by the requirements of the Jones Act, which generally requires that goods be transported between places within the U.S., including between the mainland U.S. west coast and Hawaii, using only U.S.-owned, built, and crewed ships.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Jones Act-compliant vessels are often more expensive to build and operate than foreign equivalents, which can drive up shipping costs.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Therefore, Hawaii relies on receiving most inbound goods on Jones Act-qualified vessels originating from the U.S. west coast, which may contribute to the increased cost of some consumer goods and therefore the overall cost of living.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Critics of the Jones Act contend that Hawaii consumers ultimately bear the expense of transporting goods imposed by the Jones Act.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The aboriginal culture of Hawaii is Polynesian.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii represents the northernmost extension of the vast Polynesian Triangle of the south and central Pacific Ocean.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] While traditional Hawaiian culture remains as vestiges in modern Hawaiian society, there are re-enactments of the ceremonies and traditions throughout the islands.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Some of these cultural influences, including the popularity (in greatly modified form) of *lūʻau* and *hula*, and gestures such as the Shaka sign, are strong enough to affect the wider United States.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The cuisine of Hawaii is a fusion of many foods brought by immigrants to the Hawaiian Islands, including the earliest Polynesians and Native Hawaiian cuisine, and American, Chinese, Filipino, Japanese, Korean, Polynesian, Puerto Rican, and Portuguese origins.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Plant and animal food sources are imported from around the world for agricultural use in Hawaii.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] *Poi*, a starch made by pounding taro, is one of the traditional foods of the islands.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] *Spam musubi* is an example of the fusion of ethnic cuisine that developed on the islands among the mix of immigrant groups and military personnel.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In the 1990s, a group of chefs developed Hawaii regional cuisine as a contemporary fusion cuisine.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Some key customs and etiquette in Hawaii are as follows: when visiting a home, it is considered good manners to bring a small gift for one's host (for example, a dessert).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Thus, parties are usually in the form of potlucks.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Most locals take their shoes off before entering a home.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It is customary for Hawaiian families, regardless of ethnicity, to hold a luau to celebrate a child's first birthday.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It is also customary at Hawaiian weddings, especially at Filipino weddings, for the bride and groom to do a money dance (also called the pandanggo).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Print media and local residents recommend that one refer to residents of Hawaii who are not ethnically Hawaiian as "locals of Hawaii" or "people of Hawaii".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiian mythology includes the legends, historical tales, and sayings of the ancient Hawaiian people.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It is considered a variant of a more general Polynesian mythology that developed a unique character for several centuries before c.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It is associated with the Hawaiian religion, which was officially suppressed in the 19th century but was kept alive by some practitioners to the modern day.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Prominent figures and terms include Aumakua, the spirit of an ancestor or family god and Kāne, the highest of the four major Hawaiian deities.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Polynesian mythology is the oral traditions of the people of Polynesia, a grouping of Central and South Pacific Ocean island archipelagos in the Polynesian triangle together with the scattered cultures known as the Polynesian outliers.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Polynesians speak languages that descend from a language reconstructed as Proto-Polynesian that was probably spoken in the area around Tonga and Samoa in around 1000 BC.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Prior to the 15th century, Polynesian people migrated east to the Cook Islands, and from there to other island groups such as Tahiti and the Marquesas.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Their descendants later discovered the islands Tahiti, Rapa Nui, and later the Hawaiian Islands and New Zealand.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Polynesian languages are part of the Austronesian language family.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Many are close enough in terms of vocabulary and grammar to be mutually intelligible.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] There are also substantial cultural similarities between the various groups, especially in terms of social organization, childrearing, horticulture, building and textile technologies.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Their mythologies in particular demonstrate local reworkings of commonly shared tales.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Polynesian cultures each have distinct but related oral traditions; legends or myths are traditionally considered to recount ancient history (the time of "pō") and the adventures of gods ("atua") and deified ancestors.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The literature of Hawaii is diverse and includes authors Kiana Davenport, Lois-Ann Yamanaka, and Kaui Hart Hemmings.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiian magazines include *Hana Hou!*, *Hawaii Business* and *Honolulu*, among others.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The music of Hawaii includes traditional and popular styles, ranging from native Hawaiian folk music to modern rock and hip-hop.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Styles such as slack-key guitar are well known worldwide, while Hawaiian-tinged music is a frequent part of Hollywood soundtracks.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii also made a major contribution to country music with the introduction of the steel guitar.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Traditional Hawaiian folk music is a major part of the state's musical heritage.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Hawaiian people have inhabited the islands for centuries and have retained much of their traditional musical knowledge.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Their music is largely religious in nature, and includes chanting and dance music.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiian music has had an enormous impact on the music of other Polynesian islands; according to Peter Manuel, the influence of Hawaiian music is a "unifying factor in the development of modern Pacific musics".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Native Hawaiian musician and Hawaiian sovereignty activist Israel Kamakawiwoʻole, famous for his medley of "Somewhere Over the Rainbow/What a Wonderful World", was named "The Voice of Hawaii" by NPR in 2010 in its 50 great voices series.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Due to its distance from the continental United States, team sports in Hawaii are characterised by youth, collegial and amateur teams over professional teams, although some professional teams sports teams have at one time played in the state.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Notable college sports events in Hawaii include the Maui Invitational Tournament, Diamond Head Classic (basketball) and Hawaii Bowl (football).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The only NCAA Division I team in Hawaii is the Hawaii Rainbow Warriors and Rainbow Wahine, which competes at the Big West Conference (major sports), Mountain West Conference (football) and Mountain Pacific Sports Federation (minor sports).
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] There are three teams in NCAA Division II: Chaminade Silverswords, Hawaii Pacific Sharks and Hawaii-Hilo Vulcans, all of which compete at the Pacific West Conference.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Surfing has been a central part of Polynesian culture for centuries.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Since the late 19th century, Hawaii has become a major site for surfists from around the world.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Notable competitions include the Triple Crown of Surfing and The Eddie.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Likewise, Hawaii has produced elite-level swimmers, including five-time Olympic medalist Duke Kahanamoku and Buster Crabbe, who set 16 swimming world records.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii has produced a number of notable Mixed Martial Arts fighters, such as former UFC Lightweight Champion and UFC Welterweight Champion B.J.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Penn, and former UFC Featherweight Champion Max Holloway.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Other notable Hawaiian Martial Artists include Travis Browne, K.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Noons, Brad Tavares and Wesley Correira.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaiians have found success in the world of sumo wrestling.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Takamiyama Daigorō was the first foreigner to ever win a sumo title in Japan, while his protege Akebono Tarō became a top-level sumo wrestler in Japan during the 1990s before transitioning into a successful professional wrestling career in the 2000s.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Akebono was the first foreign-born Sumo to reach Yokozuna in history and helped fuel a boom in interest in Sumo during his career.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Tourism is an important part of the Hawaiian economy as it represents a quarter of the economy.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to the Hawaii Tourism: 2019 Annual Visitor Research Report, a total of 10,386,673 visitors arrived in 2019 which increased 5% from the previous year, with expenditures of almost $18 billion.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] In 2019, tourism provided over 216,000 jobs statewide and contributed more than $2 billion in tax revenue.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Due to mild year-round weather, tourist travel is popular throughout the year.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Tourists across the globe visited Hawaii in 2019 with over 1 million tourists from the U.S.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] East, almost 2 million Japanese tourists, and almost 500,000 Canadian tourists.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] It was with statehood in 1959 that the Hawaii tourism industry began to grow.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to Hawaiian scholar Haunani-Kay Trask, tourism in Hawaii has led to the commodification and exploitation of Hawaiian culture resulting in insidious forms of "cultural prostitution".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii has been used to fuel ideas of escapism yet tourism in Hawaii ignores the harm Kanaka and locals experience.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Cultural traditions such as the hula have been made "ornamental ... a form of exotica" for tourists as a way for large corporations and land owners to gain profit over the exploitation of Hawaiian people and culture.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Tourism in Hawaii has been considered as an escape from reality resulting in the dismissal of violence faced by Native Hawaiians and locals living on the land.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] According to scholar Winona LaDuke, native Hawaiians have been forced to gather "shrimp and fish from ponds sitting on resort property".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Tourism has also had damaging effects on the environment such as water shortages, overcrowding, sea level rising, elevated sea surface temperatures and micro plastics on beaches.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, tourism in Hawaii came to a halt, which allowed the land, water, and animals to began to heal.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Fish such as the baby akule and big ulua returned after years of not being around the bay.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The coral reefs, fish, water growth, and limu (algae) growth was able to flourish without the impact of tourism.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] There has been pushback against tourism by Native Hawaiians, urging people not to visit the islands.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] A survey by the Hawaii Tourism Authority indicated over two-thirds of Hawaiians did not want tourists to return to Hawaii.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Tourism had "become extractive and hurtful, with tourists coming here and taking, taking, taking, taking, without any reciprocation with locals".
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The annual Merrie Monarch Festival is an international Hula competition.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Hawaii International Film Festival is the premier film festival for Pacific rim cinema.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Honolulu hosts the state's long-running LGBT film festival, the Honolulu Rainbow Film Festival.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] As of 2009, Hawaii's health care system insures 92% of residents.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Under the state's plan, businesses are required to provide insurance to employees who work more than twenty hours per week.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Heavy regulation of insurance companies helps reduce the cost to employers.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Due in part to heavy emphasis on preventive care, Hawaiians' total health care expenses measured as a percentage of state GDP are substantially lower.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Proponents of universal health care elsewhere in the U.S. sometimes use Hawaii as a model for proposed federal and state health care plans.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Hawaii has the only school system within the U.S. that is unified statewide.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Policy decisions are made by the fourteen-member state Board of Education, which sets policy and hires the superintendent of schools, who oversees the Hawaii Department of Education.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Department of Education is divided into seven districts; four on Oʻahu and one for each of the other three counties.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] Public elementary, middle and high school test scores in Hawaii are below national averages on tests mandated under the No Child Left Behind Act.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] The Hawaii Board of Education requires all eligible students to take these tests and report all student test scores.
[src:aloha-festivals/hawaii-p02] This may have unbalanced the results that reported in August 2005 that of 282 schools across the state, 185 failed to reach federal minimum performance standards in mathematics and reading.
